<!-- Async WordPress.com Remote Login -->
<script id="wpcom_remote_login_js">
var wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth = '';
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( element_id ) {
	var dom_node = document.getElementById( element_id );
	if ( dom_node ) { dom_node.remove(); }
}
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( class_name ) {
	var dom_nodes = document.querySelectorAll( '.' + class_name );
	for ( var i = 0; i < dom_nodes.length; i++ ) {
		dom_nodes[i].remove();
	}
}
function wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup() {
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( "wpcom_remote_login_msg" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_js" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_iframe" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_styles" );
}

// Watch for messages back from the remote login
window.addEventListener( "message", function( e ) {
	if ( e.origin === "https://r-login.wordpress.com" ) {
		var data = {};
		try {
			data = JSON.parse( e.data );
		} catch( e ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
			return;
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN' ) {
			// Clean up the login check iframe
			wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );

			var id_regex = new RegExp( /^[0-9]+$/ );
			var token_regex = new RegExp( /^.*|.*|.*$/ );
			if (
				token_regex.test( data.token )
				&& id_regex.test( data.wpcomid )
			) {
				// We have everything we need to ask for a login
				var script = document.createElement( "script" );
				script.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
				script.src = '/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=validate'
					+ '&wpcomid=' + data.wpcomid
					+ '&token=' + encodeURIComponent( data.token )
					+ '&host=' + window.location.protocol
						+ '//' + window.location.hostname;
				document.body.appendChild( script );
			}

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, not logged in, so redirect
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REDIRECT' ) {
			window.location = 'https://wordpress.com/log-in?redirect_to=' + window.location.href;
			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, storage access failed, remove the request
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REMOVE' ) {
			var css_zap = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) { html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } }';
			var style_zap = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style_zap.type = 'text/css';
			style_zap.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css_zap ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style_zap );

			var e = document.getElementById( 'wpcom_request_access_iframe' );
			e.parentNode.removeChild( e );

			document.cookie = 'wordpress_com_login_access=denied; path=/; max-age=31536000';

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP
		if ( data.msg === 'REQUEST_ACCESS' ) {
			console.log( 'request access: safari' );

			// Check ITP iframe enable/disable knob
			if ( wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth !== 'safari_itp_iframe' ) {
				return;
			}

			// If we are in a "private window" there is no ITP.
			var private_window = false;
			try {
				var opendb = window.openDatabase( null, null, null, null );
			} catch( e ) {
				private_window = true;
			}

			if ( private_window ) {
				console.log( 'private window' );
				return;
			}

			var iframe = document.createElement( 'iframe' );
			iframe.id = 'wpcom_request_access_iframe';
			iframe.setAttribute( 'scrolling', 'no' );
			iframe.setAttribute( 'sandbox', 'allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation' );
			iframe.src = 'https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=request_access&origin=' + encodeURIComponent( data.origin ) + '&wpcomid=' + encodeURIComponent( data.wpcomid );

			var css = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 46px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 46px !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 660px ) { html { margin-top: 71px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 71px !important; } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { display: block; height: 71px !important; } } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { border: 0px; height: 46px; position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; min-width: 100%; z-index: 99999; background: #23282d; } ';

			var style = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style.type = 'text/css';
			style.id = 'wpcom_request_access_styles';
			style.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style );

			document.body.appendChild( iframe );
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'DONE' ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
		}
	}
}, false );

// Inject the remote login iframe after the page has had a chance to load
// more critical resources
window.addEventListener( "DOMContentLoaded", function( e ) {
	var iframe = document.createElement( "iframe" );
	iframe.style.display = "none";
	iframe.setAttribute( "scrolling", "no" );
	iframe.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	iframe.src = "https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php"
		+ "?wpcom_remote_login=key"
		+ "&origin=aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGFja2xpc3RkZWNsYXNzaWZpZWQubmV0"
		+ "&wpcomid=9473618"
		+ "&time=1603821669";
	document.body.appendChild( iframe );
}, false );
</script>

		function addLoadEvent(func) {
			var oldonload = window.onload;
			if (typeof window.onload != 'function') {
				window.onload = func;
			} else {
				window.onload = function () {
					oldonload();
					func();
				}
			}
		}

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:1 Dr Hans Koehler (‚Ññ 33)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Where we‚Äôre at </b>: Season 5 ended with a mad chase between Liz and Red to claim a duffel bag of bones. At the end of the chase, Red walked away with the prize ~ the answer to a secret he has been trying to keep from Liz. In the course of the series, many people have died trying to get the duffel to Liz and keep it away from Red, including, most importantly, her husband Tom and Mr Kaplan, Red‚Äôs cleaner and Liz‚Äôs one-time nanny. Red takes the duffel to the homestead of Liz‚Äôs maternal grandfather Dom, an infamous former KGB operative once known by the codename Oleander. Liz‚Äôs mother also was a KGB spy. Liz once met Dom but he and Red have kept her relationship with Dom a secret. At Dom‚Äôs homestead, Red has now incinerated the skeleton, with Dom remarking, ‚ÄúShe may not know your secret, but she knows you&#8217;ve got one. She&#8217;s never gonna let it go.‚Äù</p>
<p>However, unbeknownst to Red and Dom, Liz has collaborated with her half-sister Jennifer (also by Raymond Reddington) to purloin the duffel bag before he claimed it. In addition to the skeleton, it contained a DNA report which identified the bones as being those of ~ Raymond Reddington! This is the big secret. The man we have known as Raymond ‚ÄúRed‚Äù Reddington appears to be an imposter! Liz and Jennifer have just one goal now: to find out who the man is who assumed the identity of Raymond Reddington 30 years ago ‚Äì and to exact their revenge.
</p></blockquote>

<b>Red:</b> The last thing I want is to push you away. So if we need a little truth and reconciliation to prevent that, well, what the hell? Just don&#8217;t get greedy.<br />
Liz: [ SCOFFS ] You&#8217;re serious?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You want to know my secrets, why I&#8217;m here, what the good doctor told me?<br />
Liz: Yes, I do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Then I&#8217;ll tell you. As soon as you tell me.<br />
Liz: Tell you what? <a id="return"></a><br />
<b>Red:</b> The secrets you keep from me.<br />
Liz: I never said I kept any.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Studies show that at any given moment the average person is keeping 13 secrets. <a href="#triviakey">üîò [ See Note ] </a> So come on. I actually think this could be quite fun. I&#8217;ll tell you mine if you tell me yours.<br />
Liz: This isn&#8217;t a game.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It could be. If the secrets you keep are as loving as the ones Dembe keeps.<br />
[ Liz doesn‚Äôt say anything ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] Well. That is interesting.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ressler walks over ]<br />
Ressler: The ID on the dead guy turned up as fake, but we sent the prints to Interpol and we got a hit.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell me.<br />
Ressler: Not until you tell us why you gave us this case, because it obviously wasn&#8217;t so we could arrest Dr. Koehler and expose his clients.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hans Koehler was a friend of mine. I suspected he was being held against his will. I wanted to save his life. Sadly, I failed.<br />
Liz: You cared about him? You expect us to believe that&#8217;s all that&#8217;s going on here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> All? No. Enough? Certainly. The guard. Who was he?<br />
Ressler: A known associate of Bastien Moreau.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Corsican.<br />
Samar: Until four months ago, no one knew who The Corsican was. Then he shows up on a camera in Gdansk and is ID&#8217;d as Moreau.<br />
Ressler: Which explains his sudden urge to pay a visit on Dr. Makeover.<br />
<b>Red:</b> One of the world&#8217;s deadliest assassins is now one of the world&#8217;s most anonymous men. Which means he can act with impunity. Whatever he is up to I fear Dr. Koehler is only the beginning.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Reagan International Airport ] [ Moreau and his guards are in the parked SUV ]<br />
Guard: The Feds have Gabin&#8217;s body. They&#8217;ll connect him to you.<br />
Moreau: [ LAUGHS ] To who I was. Not to who I am. The assignment remains. This changes nothing. We travel as planned. Well, at least I travel as planned.<br />
[ SILENCED GUNSHOTS (üí•üí•) ]<br />
[ Morea gets out, opens the trunk and pulls out a wheelchair and puts on a fake cast and a baseball cap. He rolls himself along in the wheelchair ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: All right. The Corsican is a gun for hire. But not by just anyone. He has a very particular clientele. The Tamil Tigers. The Kosovo Liberation Army. He&#8217;s a nationalist who works on behalf of groups fighting against globalism.<br />
Ressler: His targets have included a UNESCO office in Geneva, a conference center in Davos, and the European Union headquarters in The Hague, where last year a bomb was defused moments before the General Assembly&#8217;s opening session.<br />
Cooper: Before now, everything has been overseas.<br />
Ressler: Well, his next target could be here or maybe he&#8217;s already left the country.<br />
Cooper: Can&#8217;t lock down the airports. We have no idea who we&#8217;re looking for.<br />
Samar: The Corsican, as bad as he may be, is only one name on Dr. Koehler&#8217;s client list. Shouldn&#8217;t we be focused on finding the list?<br />
Liz: We may not know what this guy looks like, but thanks to Samar shooting out his taillight, we were able to trace his car.<br />
Ressler: First day back, and you&#8217;re already showing us up.<br />
Liz: It was found in a remote lot at Reagan International. There were two bodies identified at the scene matching the men you saw driving away in The Corsican&#8217;s car.<br />
Samar:  Why would he kill his own people?<br />
Liz: Same reason he killed Koehler and his team ‚Äì. they knew what he looked like. They were the only remaining ones who did.<br />
Cooper: Aram, pull every feed from that lot you can find. If you get a hit, circulate it to TSA. We&#8217;ll find that list, but right now we&#8217;ve got an emergency on our hands. Get to Reagan, coordinate with Airport Authority Police, tell them we&#8217;ve got a situation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the airport, Moreau has just passed through the TSA scanner ]<br />
TSA Agent: All right, sir.<br />
Moreau: Thanks.<br />
TSA Agent: [ To next person ] Wait there, ma&#8217;am.<br />
[ An airport escort is pushing Moreau‚Äôs wheelchair now ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Samar makes call to airport security as Ressler drives ]<br />
Samar: Two minutes out. Moreau, Bastien. I need you to notify security he&#8217;s on site and Yes, that&#8217;s exactly what I&#8217;m saying. No, I do not have a positive ID, but you need to put the facility on lockdown and hold all passengers.<br />
&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Man on (escort‚Äôs) radio</b>: Code three, all responders. White male. Mid-50s. May be armed.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Moreau: Sir, I&#8217;m terribly sorry. Can we please stop at the men&#8217;s room before getting to my gate?<br />
Escort: Of course, sir. Not a problem.<br />
Moreau: Thank you.</p>
<blockquote><p>
Woman on PA: We ask for your assistance in reporting any unattended bags.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Ressler and Samar arrive at the airport ]<br />
Ressler: Lock it down. All points of exit. Drop-off, pick-up, parking garages, everywhere.<br />
Samar: Agent Navabi, FBI. I need you take me to your C.O. I need every male passenger searched, ID&#8217;d, and taken to a secure area. Where are your security feeds?<br />
Man: Over here.<br />
[ RADIO CHATTER ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Moreau has ditched the wheelchair and is on foot. He is wearing the maroon blazer of the escort service. Ressler is about the follow him, when a man comes up to him ]<br />
Man: Sir! We need you right away. We got something.<br />
[ The escort lies on the floor of the men‚Äôs room ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Man on radio</b>: All units, suspect is impersonating an airport employee in a maroon blazer. Attention, all units.
</p></blockquote>
<p>‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Moreau enters the escort services parking area, grabs keys for a car from the board. He smashes the window of a vehicle and gets in </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Man on radio</b>: ‚Ä¶ white male suspect ‚Ä¶
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ DOOR CLOSES ] [ ENGINE STARTS ] [ Moreau leaves in the vehicle ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Mrs Koehler: Yes?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mrs Koehler, I&#8217;m terribly sorry for your loss.<br />
Mrs Koehler: How did‚Äì Who are you?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A friend of your husband&#8217;s. My name is Raymond. I&#8217;m here for the Picasso.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Picasso is the Koehlers‚Äô stuffed dog; a real dog who was stuffed, that is ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well. This is unexpected.<br />
Mrs Koehler: Why would Hans want you to take him? He loved Picasso.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How much do you know about your husband&#8217;s line of work?<br />
Mrs Koehler: He was a great surgeon.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He was away for months at a time, wasn&#8217;t he?<br />
Mrs Koehler: He had clients all over the world.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He did. Many of those clients were criminals. Some of them terrible men and terrible women.<br />
Mrs Koehler: That&#8217;s not so.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It is. I should know. I&#8217;m one of them.<br />
[ Red examines the stuffed dog. In its collar is a thumb drive ]<br />
Mrs Koehler: What is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your husband&#8217;s client list.<br />
Mrs Koehler: That&#8217;s what you came for.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. And to give you this. It&#8217;s a numbered bank account with $5 million in it and also the name of a man who&#8217;s standing by to create your false identification.<br />
Mrs Koehler: [ EXHALES SHARPLY ] I don&#8217;t understand.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Other clients will come looking for this list. I don&#8217;t know how many or when. Just that they will. And you do not want to be here when they do.<br />
Mrs Koehler: Why are you doing this?<br />
<b>Red:</b> As I said, Hans was a friend of mine. I wouldn&#8217;t be the person I am if it weren&#8217;t for him. I recommend Cairo. Beautiful, historic. And thanks to a combination of the Muslim Brotherhood and international Islamophobia, completely abandoned by Western tourists. You and Picasso will have the pyramids to yourselves.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: So let me get this straight. We lost Moreau.<br />
Ressler: He slipped security using the identity of an airline rep.<br />
Samar: Security feeds show him stealing a car from an employee parking lot. We have word out on the vehicle now.<br />
Cooper: Any hits?<br />
Aram: Not yet.<br />
Cooper: So he&#8217;s gone, and Koehler is dead, and the names of his clients died with him.<br />
Liz: All except Moreau.<br />
Cooper: Who&#8217;s God knows where and about to do God knows what.<br />
Liz: Reddington never wanted us to catch Koehler.<br />
Cooper: Any chance he told you what it was?<br />
Liz: [ SCOFFS ] No. He didn&#8217;t.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Liz: I did.<br />
Cooper: And have you made a decision?<br />
Liz: The Raymond Reddington we know can&#8217;t be trusted. But there was another Reddington.<br />
Cooper: Another Reddington?<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s hard to explain, but I want to know how the Reddington we could trust turned into the one we can&#8217;t. I have to know. Whatever the price.</p>

[ Baptist Generals‚Äô ‚ô™ ‚ÄúTurnunders and Overpasses‚Äù plays ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> An insurance policy. Dr. Koehler was a not only a gifted surgeon, but also a man smart enough to know that his life was threatened by the very men and women who paid for his services. For that reason, he kept a dossier ‚Äì a list of every face he changed.<br />
Liz: Moreau knew about this.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Which is why he abducted Dr. Koehler and his team and forced them to operate at gunpoint.<br />

<b>Red:</b> No. But the names of countless others are men and women who abandoned their lives to hide. Now you can find them.<br />
Liz: Where to find this ‚Äì that&#8217;s what Dr. Koehler whispered to you before he died.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I told you mine. Now you tell me yours.<br />
Liz: I would. But you haven&#8217;t really told me yours yet, have you? Not all of it. This isn&#8217;t the complete list, is it?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, it&#8217;s not. One file has been deleted.<br />
Liz: Yours.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ SIGHS ] I prefer to keep my nips and tucks to myself. Forgive an old man his vanity.<br />
Liz: For now, but someday I want to see the before and after pictures.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] Not a pretty sight.m<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sure you were always handsome.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Was I? I can&#8217;t remember.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:2 The Corsican (‚Ññ 20)</h3>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Where we‚Äôre at: </b> Liz and Lilly (aka Jennifer) have located the foundation of a house in Rehoboth Beach, Delaware, which was the place where the fire happened which Liz remembers in flashbacks and nightmares, of the night on which she as a four-year-old shot and killed their father. They want to learn the true identity of the man who afterwards assumed their father‚Äôs identity, the man we know as Raymond ‚ÄúRed‚Äù Reddington. Everyone on the task force now knows that a skeleton was in the duffel bag (chased in Season 5) and Red believes that Liz ‚Äúhas come to terms‚Äù with its identity being one of Red‚Äôs secrets. Only Liz and Lilly know there was a DNA report with the skeleton identifying it as that of the real Raymond Reddington, matching the DNA sample Cooper took from a 30 year old shirt from a torture scene from which Cooper had rescued the original Raymond Reddington and which linked Liz with that Raymond Reddington as daughter and father. Liz still publicly acknowledges Red as her father, preferring to keep the secret she shares with Lilly from both Red and the Task Force.</p>
<p>Liz and Lilly found a news report of the fire and are attempting to get medical records of anyone treated in a nearby hospital afterwards. At the same time, Red is attempting to erase any traces of who he was in that distant past, beginning with Dr Hans Koehler who performed plastic surgery on him. He offered the case to the task force suggesting that locating Dr Koehler could help them identify the many criminals whose identities Dr Koehler changed. </p>
<p>They discovered that Koehler was being held captive along with his surgical team and required to perform face-altering surgery on an infamous anti-globalism terrorist named Bastien Moreau, nicknamed The Corsican. They arrived too late to save Dr Koehler‚Äôs life, but not before Koehler could give Red the key to obtaining his client list. Red turned over the list to Liz but admitted to her he had deleted one record ‚Äì his own. Meanwhile, The Corsican has a new face and is on to his next assignment.

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:3 The Pharmacist (‚Ññ 124)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red is under arrest! Not by the federal government with which he has an immunity agreement, but by the aggressive Southern District of New York. The fact he just revealed and foiled an attempt to bomb the United Nations looks to hold no sway there. Nor have Cooper‚Äôs attempts to get Panabaker to step in, or to get the US Attorney for the SDNY to stand down. </p>
<p>Worse, the tip as to Red‚Äôs whereabouts came from an unlikely source ‚Äì Liz. Lilly has convinced Liz that this is the only way they will ever be able to find out who Red really is ‚Äì this man who assumed the identity of their father, Raymond Reddington, 30 years ago. But Liz now has grave doubts when she considers all the good Red has been capable of and all the lives he has saved. Red‚Äôs preoccupation is only with finding out who betrayed him, a task for which he turns for help to ‚Äì (wait for it:) Liz.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ GRAVEL SCRAPING ] [ A man shuffles slowly and unsteadily toward a large warehouse ]<br />
[ Caught A Ghost‚Äôs ‚ô™ &#8220;Footsteps&#8221; plays ]<br />
[ A small wooden window opens in the door ]<br />
Man: Name?<br />
Walter Pruitt: [ BREATHLESSLY ] Walter Pruitt.<br />
[ His name is crossed off a list of five names ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Get out the door<br />
And smell the sulfur hanging in the air
</p></blockquote>
<p>Man: Name?<br />
Margaret Hopkins: [ SHAKILY ] Margaret Hopkins.<br />
[ Her name is also crossed off ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Get out to work<br />
Turning the page as if there&#8217;s nothing there<br />
I often wonder ‚Äì
</p></blockquote>
<p>Man: Name?<br />
Dan: [ Shaking and stuttering ] D-D-Dan ‚Äì<br />
[ The name Daniel Lloyd is crossed off ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ If I ever felt another way<br />
I&#8217;ve never known another life<br />
There goes another day<br />
Vaguely revolutionary songs and incantations
</p></blockquote>

[ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
[ Patients are on gurneys hooked to monitoring equipment. They are arranged in a circle inside a large vinyl enclosure ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Fighting battles from the basement<br />
You slept through the alarm
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Spalding Stark leans on a cane and speaks with a shaky voice ]<br />
Spalding Stark: Thank you all for coming.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Afraid we got complacent
</p></blockquote>
<p>Stark: I know it wasn&#8217;t easy to get here ‚Äì </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Micro-managing behaviors
</p></blockquote>
<p>Stark: ‚Äì in your current condition.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Painting shades of gray
</p></blockquote>
<p>Stark: On the bright side, you won&#8217;t be in your current condition for much longer.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ When darkness had an army
</p></blockquote>
<p>Stark: To be clear, the procedure that we suggest today has not been approved by the FDA. In fact, you&#8217;ll each have to inject yourselves. It&#8217;s a crime for us to do it for you. We ask that you administer the treatment at the same time.<br />
[ INJECTORS FIRING ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ They told you you could have everything<br />
If you just believe<br />

</p></blockquote>

</p></blockquote>
<p>Margaret: Oh! Oh! </p>

‚ô™ Is even yours to make
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ LAUGHTER ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ You hear it happens<br />
If you get down on your knees and beg
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ LAUGHING CONTINUES, MONITOR BEEPING RAPIDLY ]<br />
Assistant: He&#8217;s seizing.<br />
[ RAPID BEEPING CONTINUES ] [ MEN GROANING ] [ FLATLINING ] [ GROANING CONTINUES ] [ PADDLES WHINING ] [ THUMP ] [ FLATLINING ] [ FLATLINING CONTINUES ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOOR SLIDES SHUT ] [ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS IN DISTANCE ] [ Liz speaks to Red in his pre-trial detention cell ]<br />
Liz: Cooper talked to the Attorney General this morning. Officially, your Immunity Agreement never existed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> They won&#8217;t let me see Marvin Gerard.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sure there are other lawyers.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m being denied my counsel of choice.<br />
Liz: A public defender&#8217;s been assigned for the arraignment. Did you hear what I said? Cooper&#8217;s been ordered not to inform the court about the Task Force. They&#8217;re going to prosecute you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course they are. They&#8217;re political animals. In the short run, justice always loses to politics.<br />
Liz: Aren&#8217;t you worried? You&#8217;ve been indicted for at least half a dozen capital offenses.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m confident I&#8217;ll prevail. I want to talk about the news. The Marshals have been watching all morning.<br />
Liz: Yeah, you&#8217;ve been the top story on every channel.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m not talking about me. There was a story about bodies found in a Virginia warehouse.<br />
Liz: I saw that. Some kind of underground medical experiment?<br />
<b>Red:</b> What if I told you I knew who conducted that experiment? His name is Dr. Spalding Stark, and he&#8217;s the next name on the Blacklist.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re facing the death penalty, and you&#8217;re giving us a case?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Spalding Stark speaks with a patient ]<br />
Stark: Rigidity. Bradykinesis. Yes. I&#8217;m certain our treatment can help.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dr Stark presents as as renegade, a biohacker, devoutly dedicated to enhancing human life by hacking our genetics.<br />
Liz: What do you mean he &#8220;presents&#8221; that way?<br />
<b>Red:</b> He approached a company of mine about a year ago, asked for help acquiring some advanced gene-editing equipment. I must say, he was very convincing.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ames: [ SHAKILY ] It&#8217;s just so expensive.<br />
Stark: I know. I&#8217;m sorry. But we&#8217;re doing this on our own, without the R&amp;D budget of a big pharmaceutical powerhouse.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> Some of our most revolutionary scientific achievements come from minds outside the mainstream. I helped him because I thought ‚Äì he was quite possibly a visionary.<br />
Liz: And now?<br />
<b>Red:</b> And now there are five dead bodies in a warehouse suggesting otherwise. Now I fear Stark may be the worst kind of charlatan, the kind who preys on the weakest among us for his own financial gain.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ames: My- My daughter&#8217;s pregnant. I want to see my grandchild. [ BREATHING SHAKILY ] I can get you the money.<br />
Stark: Hm.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Courthouse ] [ DOOR CREAKS ]<br />
Court Clerk: All rise! United States versus Raymond Reddington. C-R 18-3656. Magistrate Judge Roberta Wilkins now presiding.<br />
Sima: Morning, Your Honor. Assistant US Attorney Michael Sima ‚Äì for the United States.<br />
Lonnergan: Jerome Lonnergan from the Office of the Federal Public Defender for the accused.<br />
Uh, waive reading of the rights and charges, ‚Äì but not the rights thereunder.<br />
Judge Wilkins: So waived.<br />
Sima: Your Honor, given the defendant&#8217;s history, the government asks that he be remanded.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Yeah, I&#8217;m gonna calendar this for a month from today.<br />
Lonnergan: A month from today would be just perfect, Your Honor. Thank you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Y-Your Honor, may I be heard?<br />
Judge Wilkins: I don&#8217;t recommend it, Mr. Reddington. You have an attorney. I strongly suggest you let him do the talking.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And I would, Your Honor, no question, but given how quickly things are proceeding, I get the distinct impression that Jerry here has a bus to catch.<br />
Judge Wilkins: I&#8217;m sorry. Are we moving too fast for you, Mr. Reddington?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] I&#8217;m just saying there are important matters to discuss.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Such as?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, for starters, Your Honor hasn&#8217;t really considered the issue of bail.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Sir, you have been a federal fugitive for nearly three decades, the FBI&#8217;s Number One Most Wanted. You are the textbook definition of a flight risk and a danger to the community.<br />
Now, let me be clear ‚Äì even if you were prepared to submit every last dollar in circulation on the planet, I still wouldn&#8217;t grant you bail, ever.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Okay. I, for one, feel better knowing it was considered.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Anything else?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m afraid so. May we approach?<br />
Judge Wilkins: Carefully.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You hang here, Jerry. This will only take a sec.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Look at my face, Mr. Reddington. I&#8217;m not amused.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And I assure you, neither am I. But the fact remains the prosecution has intentionally failed to inform the court of a critical factor in this case.<br />
Judge Wilkins: And that is?<br />
<b>Red:</b> My Immunity Agreement with the federal government, an agreement that expressly covers the charges before you and protects me from overzealous beavers like Mr. Sima and his bosses.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Good Lord. You&#8217;re a confidential informant. Mr. Sima?<br />
Sima: I-If If there&#8217;s an agreement, I haven&#8217;t seen any evidence to prove it.<br />
Judge Wilkins: That&#8217;s hardly a denial. Mr. Reddington, is there anything you can offer this court to support the existence of an Immunity Agreement?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Assistant Director Harold Cooper of the FBI is here. He may be able to shed some light on the matter.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Assistant Director Cooper, step up, please. Sir. Mr. Cooper, I&#8217;m going to ask you this once and only once. To your knowledge, is there currently an Immunity Agreement in place with this defendant? Yes or no?<br />
Cooper: Yes.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Chambers, all of you, now!<br />
[ GAVEL POUNDS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOOR CREAKS LIGHTLY ]<br />
Judge Wilkins: [ SIGHS ] You. Talk.<br />
[ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
Cooper: I run a task force. Officially, it doesn&#8217;t exist. Its purpose is to arrest high-priority targets using intelligence obtained from Mr. Reddington.<br />
Judge Wilkins: So, Main Justice made a deal with the devil himself?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] Shouldn&#8217;t judges at least pretend to be impartial?<br />
Sima: Your Honor, as I said, if such a deal exists‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, it exists. Harold and I have been at this for over five years now. Of course, some of the people who originally approved it are either dead or have moved on, leaving Director Cooper to deal with the cover-their-asses crowd, who, by the way, are perfectly happy to milk this cow all the way to the slaughterhouse. I&#8217;m sure the first question they asked in response to my arrest was whether I could still continue to be an effective asset while locked up in jail ‚Äì am I right, Harold?<br />
Judge Wilkins: Mr. Cooper, you tell your superiors at Main Justice that I just ordered a hearing on the scope of the agreement, and I want a copy of it on my desk today. I can&#8217;t rule on a contract I haven&#8217;t seen. Understood? Good. We&#8217;ll reconvene in the morning. Mr. Reddington, you have an attorney sitting out there who has no idea what he&#8217;s gotten into. I suggest you fill him in.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Actually, I don&#8217;t think that&#8217;ll be necessary.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Why is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because after careful consideration of the circumstances, I feel it more prudent to represent myself.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram is at the Post Office talking to Samar and Ressler in their vehicle ]<br />
Aram: His name is Spalding Stark. This guy is, like, a total icon in the biohacking community.<br />
Samar: There are icons in the biohacking community?<br />

Judge Wilkins: So, here we are at the end of a hearing nobody wanted me to have about an agreement nobody wanted me to see. It&#8217;s times like these I&#8217;m grateful that federal judges are appointed for life. I&#8217;m not as brave as Director Cooper. I agree with Mr. Sima. There are certain actions that fall beneath the standard our citizens have the right to expect from a country that prides itself on the rule of law. I honestly don&#8217;t know whether Mr. Reddington is guilty of the multitude of crimes with which he&#8217;s been charged. He&#8217;s never been tried. That is the problem.<br />
To deem this deal the abomination that Mr. Sima would have me believe, I&#8217;d have to first accept that Mr Reddington is the monster he&#8217;s alleged to be. Our Constitution requires otherwise. I don&#8217;t like this deal. But like it or not, the federal government has benefited from it for over five years. They can&#8217;t pretend they haven&#8217;t, and neither will I. Accordingly, this court finds Mr. Reddington&#8217;s Immunity Agreement legally binding.<br />
[ An assistant whispers to Sima ]<br />
Sima: Objection, Your Honor.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Your Honor. We really should do this again some time.<br />
Sima: Your Honor? May I be heard, Your Honor?<br />
Judge Wilkins: Mr. Sima, your objection is noted. The agreement stands.<br />
Sima: Then he violated it.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Excuse me?<br />
Sima: The agreement bars us from prosecuting the defendant unless he violated it. Under the terms, we would then have a right to declare it null and void.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, please. Violated it how?<br />
Sima: The gun. When you were arrested, you had an unregistered weapon in your possession.<br />
<b>Red:</b> But that&#8217;s a state crime.<br />
Sima: Yes, right up until someone scratched the serial number off of it. That made it a federal offense.<br />
Judge Wilkins: He&#8217;s right, Mr. Reddington. I don&#8217;t imagine this agreement lets you walk around with a defaced firearm. If you violated your obligations under the deal, you&#8217;ve forfeited its protections.<br />
<b>Red:</b> To prove that, the gun would have to be admissible in evidence.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Why wouldn&#8217;t it be?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because the officer who seized it was conducting an unreasonable search and seizure.<br />
Judge Wilkins: I see. I take it, then, that you are moving to exclude the gun and request a suppression hearing?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am, a-and I do.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Granted. Well, look at that. Your wish came true. It seems we will get to do this again soon.</p>

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:4 The Pawnbrokers (‚Ññ 146-147)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 1/18/2019 in the US<br />

<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:4 The Pawnbrokers (‚Ññ 146-147)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): After the Department of Justice ordered Cooper to keep the Reddington Task Force and Red‚Äôs Immunity Agreement under wraps, Red stood before Judge Roberta Wilkins and declared he would be representing himself. He immediately called on Cooper about the Agreement. Under oath, Cooper had to affirm that the Agreement existed. A copy was provided to the judge. Against a withering condemnation of Red by the prosecuting attorney, Asst US Attorney Michael Sima, Cooper provided a positive account of the many criminals rounded up and crimes averted with Red‚Äôs help. In the end, the judge observed that, although  Red had been accused of many crimes, he had never stood trial or been convicted, and therefore according the Constitution, he remains innocent until proven guilty. Therefore she was ready to uphold the Immunity Agreement.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
However, the prosecutor then pointed out that Red had violated the terms of the Immunity Agreement by carrying an unregistered firearm from which the serial number had been scratched off, a federal crime. But Red claimed that the gun was inadmissible as evidence because it had been confiscated during ‚Äúan unreasonable search and seizure.‚Äù<br />
&nbsp;<br />
So Red will appear in court again, to examine the circumstances under which he was detained and his firearm seized. He believes someone tipped off the police. The new court case should give him a chance to delve into why he was arrested during the innocent act of buying a pretzel from a pretzel cart and bring him closer to determining who is was that betrayed him. In the meantime, he has been transferred to Colton Prison.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Colton Prison ]<br />
[ Red‚Äôs mug shot is taken ] [ CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS ] [ He is finger printed ]<br />
[ Delta Rae‚Äôs ‚ô™ ‚ÄúBottom of the River‚Äù plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Hold my hand<br />
Ooh, baby, it&#8217;s a long way down<br />
A long way down
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Red, in prison uniform, is given towels and soap and led on the catwalk over the dining area ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ If you get sleep or if you get none<br />
The cock&#8217;s gonna call in the morning, baby </p>
<p>‚ô™ Hold my hand<br />
Ooh, baby, it&#8217;s a long way down<br />
A long way down
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Most inmates ignore Red, except one, who scowls. Red seems to recognize him ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Oh, oh, oh<br />
Oh, oh, oh, oh<br />
Oh, oh, oh ‚Äì<br />
Oh, oh, oh, oh ‚Äì
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ The guard opens Red‚Äôs cell and Red enters ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do you smell that?<br />
Guard: Sewer line.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Would you be so kind to reach out to facilities? I&#8217;d like to put in a repair request.<br />
[ The guard locks the cell door ]<br />

<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Hold my hand </p>
<p>‚ô™ Oh, oh, oh<br />

</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Red lies on his cot, looking up. Under his head is a thin pillow and a blue cotton knit blanket, folded up. A broken pipe is in the corner of the room. Red watches a rat scurry along the edge of the room and disappear into the pipe ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Hold my hand, oh, baby<br />
It&#8217;s a long way, hold on, now<br />
Hold my hand </p>
<p>‚ô™ Ooh, baby, it&#8217;s a long way down, a long way down
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red enters the dining area. He picks up his meal and sits down across from a skinny young black guy. The black guy starts to get up ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, no, no. Please stay. I&#8217;m happy for the company. Raymond Reddington. Awaiting trial.<br />
Vontae Jones: Right. For treason. And like 200 murders.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] Such hyperbole. I don&#8217;t know whether to be flattered or horrified. What&#8217;s your name?<br />
Vontae: Jones. Vontae Jones.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hello, Vontae. Nice to meet you.<br />
Vontae: Is it true they, uh, put you in The Bunker?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ha! &#8220;The Bunker.&#8221; Is that what they call it? I&#8217;ve always wanted a home with a name. So much more evocative than a simple address. Fallingwater, the Dibble House, Sinking Spring Farm. I must say, The Bunker compares rather favorably to a Malagasy cave I once had the misfortune of inhabiting.<br />
Vontae: Don&#8217;t know what you&#8217;re talking about.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Bunker.<br />
Vontae: Ah. Warden left it for troublemakers. Smells like a dung hole.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Who&#8217;s the warden speaking with?<br />
Vontae: They call him Quantum. You ever need a hit, he&#8217;s your guy.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And if my tastes run in other directions?<br />
Vontae: Burrito ‚Äì Man over here ‚Äì do you a roll for a deuce of meat sticks and a bag of chips. And, uh, Waxer, face tats, he can fix you up with smokes, cigars, candy. He sometimes even gets cinnamon toothpicks.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, I love cinnamon toothpicks.<br />
Vontae: Yolked dude&#8217;s Baldomero. Yeah, they call him the Teflon Con &#8217;cause he&#8217;s been killing and thieving for years. Awaiting trial for knocking over a Brinks truck. Killed both guards‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m familiar with the incident.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:5 Alter Ego (‚Ññ 131)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red has ruled the block at Colton Prison, but Liz and her half-sister Lilly (Jennifer) have taken the time of his incarceration to have a geek friend mine the contents of the file of Dr Koehler‚Äôs plastic surgery patients. They want to find out who Red was before he took on the identity of their dead father, the real Raymond Reddington. The information on Red, however, has been thoroughly erased (by Red) ‚Äì except for the file names which were coded using patient-intake dates. For Red, this was October 3, 1991. They have found the file of someone who had a procedure done a couple of months later, Gerald Todd Klepper, who visited Dr. Koehler in December of 1991. They plan to track down this person to see if he crossed paths with Red. </p>
<p>Also outstanding is the question Red is bent on answering. He thinks someone may have tipped off the police. He was arrested for possessing an unregistered and defaced firearm (the serial number had been scratched off). This is a federal crime. If he is found guilty of this, his entire Immunity Agreement will be invalidated and he will face the death penalty. However, he maintains the arrest was an ‚Äúunreasonable search and seizure,‚Äù protected under the Fourth Amendment. At face value, he was simply buying pretzels at a pretzel stand. But ‚Äî <b>did</b> someone call in a tip? If so, Red is determined to find out who. The problem is ‚Äî it was his beloved Liz.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Billionnaire Harris Van Ness meets with Dembe ]<br />
Van Ness: Dembe, I trust Raymond. I do. He and I go back decades. But what the hell is going on? I wake up this morning, make an espresso, open the paper‚Äì<br />
[ Van Ness slaps down a newspaper. There is a large photo of Red being led in handcuffs, with the headline: Fugitive Criminal Sees Day In C‚Äì ]<br />
Dembe: It&#8217;s under control.<br />
Van Ness: We have hundreds of millions of dollars invested in Reddington.<br />
Dembe: Which have always returned a handsome profit.<br />
Van Ness: Your boss is looking at the death penalty. What happens if he cuts a deal?<br />
Dembe: Do you believe that Raymond would cut a deal with the FBI?<br />
Van Ness: My partners do. Carlo Androssani thinks we should cut ties with Reddington, insulate ourselves from any of the, uh, fallout.<br />
Dembe: Is that a threat?<br />
Van Ness: He called for a vote.<br />
Dembe: Can Raymond count on your support?<br />
Van Ness: I&#8217;m the least of his problems.<br />
Dembe: Does he have your vote?<br />
Van Ness: Yes. But you prepare for war. Carlo and the others  are out for blood.</p>

<p>[ There is an üî•üí•üî• Explosion üî•üí•üî• and flames engulf most of the house ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Federal Courtroom, Southern District of New York ]<br />
Judge Roberta Wilkins: This case is calendared for a 12(B) hearing. The defendant is challenging the constitutionality of a search that led to the discovery of an unregistered, defaced firearm seized from his possession. Is that correct, Mr. Reddington?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, Your Honor, on the grounds that the search was unreasonable and therefore a violation of the Fourth Amendment.<br />
Judge Wilkins: So you are familiar with Fourth Amendment jurisprudence?<br />
<b>Red:</b> One of my favorite Amendments. Top three. Maybe five.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Feel free to make light, Mr. Reddington, but this is serious business. If you lose and I allow that gun to be admitted into evidence against you, the Government will consider that a violation of your immunity agreement. And without immunity, you will be facing multiple capital offenses.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your Honor, please. I&#8217;m on pins and needles as it is, and you&#8217;re not helping the matter.<br />
Judge Wilkins: I want you to hire an attorney.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And I appreciate your concern.<br />
Judge Wilkins: It&#8217;s my obligation to let you know what you&#8217;re up against. A motion to suppress involves a complex legal analysis, one that should be done by someone with a legal education.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Which I have.<br />
Judge Wilkins: You&#8217;ll need to explain that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;re both legal professionals. Your business is to apply the law. Mine is to break it. You studied your profession. Why would you assume I haven&#8217;t studied mine?<br />
Judge Wilkins: So you&#8217;re familiar with the legal standard I&#8217;ll be using to evaluate Officer Baldwin&#8217;s search?<br />
<b>Red:</b> If you&#8217;re referring to the reasonable-suspicion standard as articulated by Justice Warren in Terry v. Ohio, I am.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Fair enough, Mr. Reddington. Though it may literally be your funeral, let&#8217;s proceed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A-Apologies, Your Honor. If I could request a brief recess.<br />
Asst US Atty Michael Sima: Oh, here we go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry. Did you say something?<br />
Sima: Let me guess. Your suit isn&#8217;t quite pressed to your liking. Or did you prefer sparkling water instead of still?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Michael, really. The process is brutal enough. I&#8217;m doing my very best despite my feelings about you. You could at least make the effort to be civil.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Denied. I see no reason to break this early, unless it&#8217;s some kind of emergency.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That it is. I need to meet with the FBI about a time-sensitive case. My immunity agreement may be in jeopardy, but while it remains intact, I intend to live up to its obligations.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The holding cell where Red stays during the court proceedings ]<br />
Liz: You can&#8217;t just pause the legal proceedings to give me a case.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have a situation.<br />
Liz: The judge is furious!<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ever since word of my capture hit the press, certain associates are looking to kick me to the curb.<br />
Liz: I know you&#8217;ve got a lot of enemies out there, but right now your biggest enemy is in that courtroom.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Harris Van Ness.<br />
Liz: What if you lose this hearing and they throw out your immunity agreem‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do you know who I&#8217;m talking about?<br />
Liz: Harris Van Ness? The billionaire big in cargo freighters, died in a fire last week.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Van Ness was murdered because of his business affiliations with me.<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re being paranoid. It was an accident.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] There are no accidents around me. Not unless they&#8217;re on purpose.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Liz: Reddington claims the explosion was a targeted hit aimed at Van Ness because he&#8217;s supporting Reddington in ongoing business dealings.<br />
Cooper: What business?<br />
Liz: Van Ness is one of a group of associates, some of whom want to sever ties with Reddington because of his arrest.<br />
Ressler: A one-percenter gets knocked off for being in league with Reddington, and now he wants us to find his killer?<br />
Samar: And Reddington has no idea who did it?<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s got a lot of enemies who want a piece of his empire.<br />
Ressler: Lucky for him, he&#8217;s got the FBI to protect it.<br />
Cooper: As for protecting Reddington, he&#8217;s our C.I. Should he ever get out of prison, we&#8217;re gonna want him to be as powerful as possible.<br />
Liz: Let&#8217;s start with the family. My guess is a man of his wealth is gonna have a lot of people coming out of the woodwork.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A man (Roger Price) leads Ressler and Liz down a corridor to the room where Van Ness‚Äôs will is to be read ]<br />
Ressler: How many people were given notice?<br />
Roger Price: 32. Mr. Van Ness had many bequests.<br />
Liz: We understand that the reading of the will can be emotional. We&#8217;ll do what we can to respect that.<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;m sorry. What&#8217;s your name? We might have some questions after we talk to the family.<br />
Roger Price: I don&#8217;t know why you&#8217;d have any questions. Paper said it was an accident.<br />
[ Roger Price opens the door ] [ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ]<br />
Roger Price: These are good people. You want to respect them? Let them mourn in peace.<br />
Ashton Hirsh (officiating): [ Reading ] &#8220;$10 million each to Human Rights Watch, the NAACP, and Brown University. The remainder of my estate I leave to my son, Timothy Peterson.&#8221;<br />
[ ATTENDEES MURMURING ]<br />
Ressler: [ Low voice ] I didn&#8217;t think Van Ness had kids.<br />
Liz: Uh, apparently neither did anyone else.<br />
Ashton Hirsh: Harris wanted this letter read along with his will. &#8220;Timothy, forgive me. I loved your mother, but I didn&#8217;t have the courage to stay with her. I know this is an awkward way to introduce you to your extended family, but it&#8217;s the only way I know how to make amends. Take the fruits of my labor and do great things. Love, your father.&#8221;<br />
[ ATTENDEES MURMURING ]<br />
[ Ashton Hirsh walks down the center aisle and hands the letter to Timothy Peterson ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs holding cell ] [ CELL DOOR CLICKS ] [ Dembe is let in to talks to Red through the bars ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah! [ LAUGHS ] What a pleasant sight.<br />
Dembe: My friend.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank goodness for the prison chaplain.<br />
Dembe: He said you designated me to provide spiritual advice.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, it had the dual benefit of getting you in here and also being true. Van Ness is dead. Without him, I don&#8217;t have the votes to prevent Androssani from cutting me off. I need you to reassure Androssani. Reason with him. And if that doesn&#8217;t work, kill him. That should scare up a vote or two.<br />
Dembe: Then what?<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;ll see.<br />
Dembe: And then what?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You do know I didn&#8217;t really ask you here to give me spiritual advice, right?<br />
Dembe: I&#8217;m going to give you some anyway. Be honest.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I need that vote.<br />
Dembe: Tell Elizabeth the truth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Everything rests on this.<br />
Dembe: Money rests on this. Power. Not peace of mind.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Something has to be done.<br />
Dembe: It is. You are fighting for your freedom. Every day I pray that you get it. For now, you must leave the rest to fate.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I make my own fate.<br />
Dembe: Not from here.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ BREATHES DEEPLY ] I&#8217;m asking you to do this.<br />
Dembe: And I am trying to save your soul.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At work, Samar is watching a video of a therapist on her computer. On another screen is a Scrabble game ]<br />
Therapist: Uh, there&#8217;s signs. The inability to recall prepositions is a common symptom of aphasia. Recommended therapies include word games, rote repetition, uh, either on your own or in a individualized, ‚Äì one-on-one, or group-therapy format.<br />
Samar: [ Softly ] Under. Above. Following.<br />
Therapist: The important thing is to start early.<br />
Samar: To. Unto. Despite. Without.<br />
[ Aram comes up behind her ]<br />
Aram: &#8220;Quetzals.&#8221; That is the national bird of Guatemala and, weirdly, one of its monetary units.<br />
Samar: Good to know.<br />
[ Samar closes the game ]<br />
Aram: No, wait, wait, wait, wait. No, no. If you put the Q and the S on the triple word score, it&#8217;s worth over 300 points.<br />
Samar: Did you find out about Timothy Peterson?<br />
Aram: Right. Work.<br />
[ Aram walks away ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram briefs the task force ]<br />
Aram: As of the reading of his father&#8217;s will, Tim Peterson is the 511th-richest man in America and, I&#8217;m fairly confident, the only billionaire working in a bowling alley and living in a trailer park. Ressler: Looks like that apple fell a few, uh, light-years from the tree.<br />
Aram: Oh, that&#8217;s putting it mildly. His credit score is 580, he&#8217;s $62,000 in debt, and he has got a criminal record.<br />
Cooped: Unpaid speeding tickets, public intoxication, a bar fight that got him thrown in jail for a week.<br />
Liz: It seems like more of a slacker than a killer.<br />
Samar: His inheritance came as a complete surprise. Then what motivation would he have to kill his father if he didn&#8217;t know about it?<br />
Aram: Well, let&#8217;s say he did know. How does a kid living in a trailer park outside Arlington connect in any way to Mr. Reddington?<br />
Ressler: And if he doesn&#8217;t, why are we even on this case?<br />

[ Helen glances at the gun on the floor ]<br />
Ressler: Don&#8217;t even think about it.<br />
[ Deidre slips out ]<br />
Ressler: Damn it.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Liz: Keen.<br />
Ressler: I got Peterson and two of the preps, but Deidre&#8217;s on the move.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ ELEVATOR BELL DINGS ] [ The doors open. Deidre is inside. Liz and Deidre fight and struggle for Liz‚Äôs gun. It goes off but misses both ] [ GUNSHOT üí• ] [‚ö°Ô∏èFighting continues‚ö°Ô∏è]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ An elderly couple waits for the elevator ]<br />
Wife: We should&#8217;ve called the bellhop, told him to bring the cart.<br />
Husband: We don&#8217;t need the cart.<br />
Wife: You say we don&#8217;t need the cart, then I carry the bags! We need the cart!<br />
Husband: Okay, next time, I&#8217;ll get the cart.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ ELEVATOR BELL DINGS ] [ The doors open and Deidre tumbles out ]<br />
[ Liz points her gun at Deidre ]<br />
Liz: Don&#8217;t move! I said don&#8217;t move! Not you, sir. Ma&#8217;am, can you please hold the door? ‚Äì [ To Deidre: ] You. Get up! [ Liz grabs Deidre and throws her back into the elevator ) [ GRUNTS ]<br />
[ The elevator doors close ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Husband: This place doesn&#8217;t get our business anymore.<br />
Wife: [ GASPS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Judge Wilkins: Uh, welcome back.I want to make a brief record. First to establish my findings, but also to preserve the facts for Mr. Reddington&#8217;s inevitable appeal. I have listened to the recording provided by the prosecution. The call is in sum and substance exactly as the resulting radio run describes. I find no compelling justification for forcing the Government to put the recording in evidence at this proceeding. Mr. Reddington, if you have any final argument, I&#8217;m ready to hear it.<br />
[ Red stands ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What did he have, Your Honor?<br />
Judge Wilkins: What did who have?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Officer Baldwin. A tip from a source who refused to give their name. No explanation as to how their information was acquired, no prior history of reliability, no compelling reason to believe the tip was even credible. And the details? A white man in his 50s wearing a suit and hat? On a busy street in New York City? I couldn&#8217;t possibly have been the only one.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;And how did the caller know I was carrying a concealed weapon? It was concealed, for God&#8217;s sake. In what stretch of the imagination could this kind of tip justify this search? Officer Baldwin obviously knew that when he got there, which is why he didn&#8217;t just throw me up against a wall. He knew that what he had didn&#8217;t amount to reasonable suspicion under the law. So what did he do? He investigated. Please excuse my drip of sarcasm, but Officer Baldwin asked for some identification, and I gave him a false ID so magnificent, even I started to believe my name was George Murphy.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;He said I looked around nervously. The truth is, I made fun of the man. I refused to give him the respect he somehow believed he deserved. It happens. I get impatient. I make a comment I might regret. It&#8217;s one of my biggest issues in therapy, along with some residual anxiety from childhood and a sexual fascination I&#8217;d prefer to discuss in chambers.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;But the point is the tip gave him next to nothing, and his own observations didn&#8217;t change things one iota. I know it, you know it, and even he knows it, which is saying a lot since I&#8217;m pretty sure all he cares about is reading his name in the papers and the whiff of his boss&#8217;s backside. Ah! You see? There I go again. I promise I will work on this with my therapist just as soon as you kick the gun and let me get the hell out of here. Thank you.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ] [ Liz sits with Tim ] [ Deidre, Marcus and Helen are led past them by police ]<br />
Tim: How could I have been so stupid?<br />
Liz: [ SIGHS ] You wanted the fantasy to be real. You wanted a family.<br />
Tim: All that time. All those lies.<br />
Liz: I know what it&#8217;s like to be fooled by people who you think are family. I know how painful that is.<br />
[ Dembe enters ]<br />
Liz: What are you doing here?<br />
Dembe: I need to speak with him.<br />
Liz: Why? This doesn&#8217;t have anything to do with Reddington.<br />
Dembe: I only need a minute.<br />
[ Liz steps aside ]<br />
Dembe: Mr. Peterson.<br />
Tim: Who are you?<br />
Dembe: I work for the man who saved your life. I&#8217;m here to ask you to do him a favor in return.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Dembe visits Red in the holding cell ]<br />
Dembe: Harris Van Ness was murdered for his money. His death had nothing to do with you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He&#8217;s still dead. When he expired, so did his vote.<br />
Dembe: It didn&#8217;t expire. It was transferred to his heir.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Van Ness doesn&#8217;t have an heir.<br />
Dembe: As fate would have it, he does.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ A board room ]<br />
Tim: My father would have voted with Reddington. In his absence, I vote with Reddington.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Dembe: You tasked the FBI to find an enemy, and in doing so, you found a friend.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What a pleasant surprise.<br />
Dembe: Sometimes you make your own fate. Sometimes fate makes you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mm.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Courtroom ]<br />
[ DOOR OPENS. Judge Wilkins enters ]<br />
Judge Wilkins: All rise. Let me be clear. Reasonable suspicion can be based upon a tip given to the police, but only if the information provided has what the Supreme Court calls &#8220;an indicia of reliability.&#8221; Now, to make that judgment, the courts look at the source&#8217;s veracity, reliability, and basis of knowledge. The officer knew none of those things. All he had was a small amount of predictive detail. White male, right age, wearing the right suit and hat. Mr. Reddington is correct. Alone, it&#8217;s not nearly enough.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;But there&#8217;s more. The officer made his own observations. In his view, the defendant seemed nervous. Whatever looks the defendant gave, he interpreted as furtive. The defendant resisted his instruction to turn around. Is that enough? It probably wouldn&#8217;t have been for me. But the issue is not whether I would have patted Mr. Reddington down. The issue is, was the decision to do so manifestly unreasonable? I find that it wasn&#8217;t. Accordingly, the defendant&#8217;s motion to suppress the gun seized from his possession is hereby denied.<br />
Sima: Your Honor, in light of your ruling, it&#8217;s our position that the defendant violated his immunity agreement.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Upon conviction for the gun possession at trial, that agreement will be nullified.<br />
Sima: We intend to pursue all of the outstanding indictments against the defendant and seek the death penalty.<br />
Judge Wilkins: One step at a time, Mr. Sima. Mr. Reddington, you made a good case. For what it&#8217;s worth, it wasn&#8217;t an easy decision.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So, I guess I&#8217;ve got that going for me.</p>

‚ô™ We were sun-burned and shoeless kids

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:6 The Ethicist (‚Ññ 91)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 1/8/2019 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="https://wp.me/pDKwi-95k" rel="nofollow">https://wp.me/pDKwi-95k</a><br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:6 The Ethicist (‚Ññ 91)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Despite Dembe‚Äôs attempts to run interference, cracks are beginning to show in Red‚Äôs business alliances, now that he is being held in prison awaiting trial. The story is being widely covered in the media. Worse, Red‚Äôs first attempt to gain his freedom has failed, with the judge ruling that the unregistered firearm he was carrying when arrested is admissible as evidence. The serial number was scratched off of the weapon, making it a federal crime. If the ruling stands on appeal, this is a felony that will invalidate his Immunity Agreement with the Department of Justice and he will have to stand trial for numerous crimes meriting the death penalty. The Judge has refused to let him personally listen to the tape recording of the tip the police received that led to his arrest. He is determined to access the recording to find out who made the call and betrayed him. (Hint: It was Liz.)</p>
<p>Liz and her half-sister Jennifer (aka Lillian Roth) plotted to have Red detained so they can learn his true identity. Red has no idea that they found out that the skeleton he thought was gone forever belonged to their father, the real Raymond Reddington. They intend to contact a man who shared the same plastic surgeon who changed Red‚Äôs identity 30 years ago when he assumed the identity of their father. The man‚Äôs name is Gerald Todd Klepper. It‚Äôs possible he remembers Red and can help unveil the mystery of Red‚Äôs true identity.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The scene of a car accident. There is a broken windshield with blood on it ]<br />
[ Dominic Halpin‚Äôs ‚ô™ ‚ÄúEverything is Fine‚Äù plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ When I feel the rain coming down on me<br />
I just brush my coat and everything&#8217;s just fine
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ A man pulls a body from the road into the brush. He comes back and picks up a broken bicycle and loads it into the trunk of his car, along with a child‚Äôs shoe. A liquor bottle lies on the floor of the trunk. In the driver‚Äôs seat, the man looks around nervously ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Big holes in my pockets where some coins, they should be<br />
[ CHUCKLES ] Hey, I&#8217;m not rich<br />
But everything&#8217;s just fine </p>
<p>‚ô™ Sometimes I talk with Mr. Blue
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The man from accident scene, Digby Tamerlane, addresses an auditorium of people ]<br />
Tamerlane: I&#8217;ve been accused of being a lot of things.<br />
[ MUSIC FADING ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ But I don&#8217;t want ‚Äì him to stay
</p></blockquote>
<p>Tamerlane: [U]nemotional, cold, a risk-inclined agitator whose own board sometimes feels he&#8217;s a liability.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ He soon goes on his way
</p></blockquote>
<p>Audience: [ LAUGHTER ]<br />
Tamerlane: Truth is, I&#8217;ve made my share of mistakes. </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Tomorrow I may wake to find
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYS ]<br />
Tamerlane: [B]ut it is no secret that our e-commerce market share is expanding much faster than anticipated. That means fulfillment is the bottleneck for real growth, which is why I am here to announce that Chione will be opening a brand-new, state-of-the-art distribution facility in Malaysia by the end of next year.<br />
[ AUDIENCE MURMURING ] [ Applause ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ People are lined up for autographs and to have their photos taken with Digby Tamerlane ]<br />
[ CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING ]<br />
Tamerlane: [ Greeting people ] All right. Oh, hey.<br />
[ CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS ]<br />
Tamerlane: All right.<br />
Gerald Todd Klepper: Mr. Tamerlane? It&#8217;s a pleasure.<br />
Tamerlane: Oh, thank you very much. Would you, uh, like a photo together?<br />
Klepper: Oh, eh, it&#8217;s okay. I&#8217;m here on business. It&#8217;s about that incident near Rock Creek Park.<br />
[ Tamerlane flashes back to the accident scene ]<br />
Tamerlane: Uh [ CHUCKLES ] ‚Äì I&#8217;m sorry, your name was?<br />
Klepper: I&#8217;m not the only one who knows. I&#8217;m afraid there&#8217;s some real legal jeopardy coming your way ‚Äì a credible witness, a grand jury.<br />
Tamerlane: Who the hell are you? How do you‚Äì<br />
Klepper: Please, let&#8217;s not talk here. Uh, just come see me alone.<br />
[ Klepper gives Tamerlane a card reading ‚ÄúNate &amp; Ted‚Äôs RV Park‚Äù ]<br />
Klepper: I think I can be of assistance.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Federal Courtroom in the Southern District of New York ]<br />
Judge Roberta Wilkins: We are on record this morning in the matter of The United States v.<br />
Raymond Reddington on charges of treason in connection to the sale of classified data to Russian Intelligence. Is the government ready to proceed to trial?<br />
Asst US Attorney Michael Sima: We are, Your Honor.<br />
Judge Wilkins: And the defense?<br />
<b>Red:</b> We are not. Uh, the royal &#8220;we&#8221; ‚Äì me. I am not.<br />
[ HORN HONKS IN DISTANCE ]<br />
Judge Wilkins: Dare I ask why?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Like it or not, I have to be open to the idea that there may be certain mental abnormalities that are the cause of my criminal conduct.<br />
Sima: As delighted as the government is that Mr. Reddington has stated on the record that his conduct is criminal, whether mental disease caused his crimes is a question for a jury to decide if and when he raises an insanity defense. I don&#8217;t see what possible connection that has to whether he&#8217;s prepared to move to trial.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, I cannot proceed to trial until I know how to [ CHUCKLING ] defend myself, or whether I can even self-advocate in an effective way.<br />
Judge Wilkins: You know the facts. That&#8217;s generally a good start.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And if the facts indicate that I&#8217;m not competent to stand trial?<br />
Sima: Defense counsel succeeded in convincing Your Honor to uphold his Immunity Agreement. H-He may be crazy like a fox‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ]<br />
Sima: ‚Äìbut he&#8217;s not crazy.<br />
<b>Red:</b> While I&#8217;ve come to appreciate the innate facility Mr. Sima has with the obvious clich√©, I&#8217;m sure the Court is aware that, on the subject of my mental health, his opinion is just that ‚Äì his opinion. I&#8217;d prefer to take the Court&#8217;s recommendation and base my defense on the facts.<br />
Judge Wilkins: The only relevant fact is that there is no motion concerning the defendant&#8217;s mental health before the court.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am making that motion now, as is my right under the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure. Therefore, I ask for the court&#8217;s indulgence because I appear before you in pro per, and also possibly mad as a hatter.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Talk about your obvious clich√©.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] Guilty as charged. Or not ‚Äì if I really am mad. How about giving us all a chance to find out? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Phone conversation ]<br />
Lilly/Jennifer: What do you mean he&#8217;s taking a trip?<br />
Liz: The judge granted his request for a psychiatric evaluation, so as a federal prisoner he&#8217;s being sent to the Federal Medical Center in Springfield, Missouri.<br />
Lilly: Does Reddington really believe anyone&#8217;s gonna think that he&#8217;s incompetent?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Inside Gerald Klepper‚Äôs RV ]<br />
Klepper: You killed someone. For that, most people would believe you belong in prison. Their belief is based on a Judeo-Christian tradition of justice. Mine is more algebraic. There&#8217;s a constant and a variable. The constant is the work you do. It has value, and it will be compromised with you behind bars. The variable is what economists call the VSL ‚Äì the value of statistical life. In this case, the value of your life versus the value of the life of the witness whose testimony will put you behind bars.<br />
Digby Tamerlane: Okay, I can make it worth their while not to say anything.<br />
Klepper: The authorities have identified her. She was walking home that night and saw what she saw. She&#8217;s made a preliminary statement. At this point, a bribe has a low probability of success. I&#8217;m afraid my equation is premised on a more permanent solution.<br />
Tamerlane: Killing her.<br />
Klepper: If her VSL is lower than yours.<br />
Tamerlane: You can&#8217;t put a price on a life.<br />
Klepper: Nearly every department in our government has a VSL. The EPA&#8217;s is $10 million. The FDA&#8217;s is $7.9 million. The Department of Transportation is $6.4 million. The annoying beep that goes off when the people in the front seat don&#8217;t put their seatbelts on? Ever wonder why there was no beep for the people sitting in the back? It would cost the auto industry $325 million a year and save 44 lives. 325 divided by 44 is 7.4 meaning that the value of each life that would be saved is $7.4 million. But since DOT values each life at only $6.4 million, no beeps in the back.<br />
Tamerlane: Those are statistical models to determine the cost of a life, not to decide the value of one life over another.<br />
Klepper: Organ recipient protocols. What a teacher makes versus a hedge fund manager. We make comparative values all the time, and I&#8217;ve done it for you and Miss Carter. A bus driver versus a titan of industry. A volunteer at a local boys&#8217; club versus a man who employs 12,000 people. I&#8217;ve circled the relevant numbers.<br />

Atticus: [ Whispering angrily ] That bitch. I- I told her I didn&#8217;t want those little red pills. I told her no.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Calm down.<br />
Atticus: I&#8217;m gonna kill that lady.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s enough, really.<br />
Atticus: I&#8217;m gonna rip that tongue right out of her mouth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Atticus, calm down.<br />
Atticus:  And once I rip that tongue out‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Atticus‚Äì<br />
Atticus: [ Yelling ] ‚ÄìI&#8217;m gonna shove it down her damn throat!<br />
[ Atticus leaps up and lunges at Dr Grey ]<br />
‚Äì Security! Security! Security!<br />
[ Red grabs Atticus‚Äôs shoulders and tries to pull him back off Dr Grey ]<br />
[ GRUNTS ] [ STRAINING ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> No! No!<br />
[ GRUNTING ]<br />
Atticus: [ YELLS ] I&#8217;m gonna rip your tongue out! I&#8217;m gonna rip your tongue out! [ YELLING ]<br />
[ Red tries to hold Atticus back until Medical Center staff manage to pull Atticus off Dr Grey and restrain him on the floor ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Lilly calls Liz at work ]<br />
Lilly: Buck is a god.<br />
Liz: He traced the phone?<br />
Lilly: He bounced the signal off of Venus or Mars ‚Äì I don&#8217;t know ‚Äì but he has a location. It&#8217;s a parking lot at 3rd and Sycamore.<br />
[ Ressler enters ]<br />
Ressler: Phone number was a dead end.<br />
Liz: [ On phone to Lilly ] I gotta go.<br />
Lilly: What are you gonna do? Are you- Are you gonna go there? Should I meet you?<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ll call you back. [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Ressler: Evidently, local PD couldn&#8217;t find Klepper&#8217;s RV. [ KEYS JANGLING ] Cooper wants us to get out there, see if anyone at the campground has information on where he might be.<br />
Liz: You go.<br />
Ressler: What ‚Äì you got someplace better to be?<br />
Liz: Yeah, I think I&#8217;m gonna try to talk to Reddington, ‚Äì see if he knows anything.<br />
Ressler: He&#8217;s in the federal psych hospital.<br />
Liz: And this is a life-or-death situation. I think they&#8217;re gonna let me talk to him.<br />
Ressler: Now, there&#8217;s a phone call I&#8217;d like to be on. I&#8217;ll get Navabi to go out to the RV parking lot‚Äì<br />
Liz: No, no, no, no, no, no, no. I mean, y-you&#8217;re welcome to listen in if you want, but, with Reddington, you catch more flies with honey, and you are definitely more sour than sweet.<br />
[ KEYS JINGLING ]<br />
Ressler: How do you do it?<br />
Liz: What?<br />
Ressler: Put up with him. I can&#8217;t stand how much he hides from us, and I&#8217;m not even his kid. I don&#8217;t know how you deal with it.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s not easy.<br />
Ressler: You make it look like it is.<br />
Liz: [ SCOFFS ]<br />
[ Ressler leaves] [ CELLPHONE DIALING ]<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ll let you know what I find out.<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;ll do the same.<br />
[ Lilly places a call; LINE RINGING ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz arrives at the RV Park and gets out of her car ]<br />
[ Car DOOR CLOSES ] [ BIRDS CHIRPING ]<br />
[ Liz raps on the door of Klepper‚Äôs RV and stands to the side ]<br />
Liz: Cameron Morella! FBI! Open the door. Mr. Morella, open the door, or a tactical team will storm your vehicle!<br />
[ Klepper (aka Cameron Morella) opens the RV door ]<br />
Liz: Hands where I can see them.<br />
[ Klepper puts his hands up and peers around outside ]<br />
Klepper: Where&#8217;s the cavalry?<br />
Liz: In my hand. Now back up.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the Federal Medical Center, the Nurse gives Atticus an injection ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, I guess there won&#8217;t be much more from him, now, will there?<br />
Nurse: That&#8217;s the idea.<br />
[ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ] [ The Nurse leaves ]<br />
[ Red taps Atticus‚Äôs chest lightly ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Atticus. Atticus. We don&#8217;t have much time.<br />
[ Red slaps his face lightly ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hey. Hey. Your friend has a job. It&#8217;s an assassination. Look at me. He knows the FBI is looking for him, so it has to be done quietly.<br />
Atticus: [ Dreamily ] I&#8217;d like to fly.<br />
[ Red slaps Atticus‚Äôs face again ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hey, hey. Hey. Your friend ‚Äì who would he turn to to get a job done as quietly as possible? Atticus, who would he turn to?<br />
Atticus: [ Sleepily ] General Shiro ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ge- General [ STAMMERING ] Who&#8217;s that? I-I don&#8217;t‚Äì General Shiro? Hey, where can I find him?<br />
Atticus: Would you like to fly? Oh. I would.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Klepper sits at the table inside the RV as Liz keeps her gun trained on him ]<br />
Liz: I know who you are, Mr. Morella. I know you murdered Kelly Carter to prevent her from telling a grand jury that she saw Digby Tamerlane trying to hide the body of a young girl he killed in a hit-and-run.<br />
Klepper: I don&#8217;t know what you&#8217;re talking about.<br />
Liz: I also know who you were, Dr. Klepper.<br />
Klepper: I don&#8217;t know that name.<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ] [ DOOR CREAKS ] [ Liz lets Lilly in. She has Klepper‚Äôs file ]<br />
Lilly: Is that him?<br />
[ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
Liz: He says no. But I think this should change his mind.<br />
[ Liz shows Klepper the file ]<br />
Liz: Look familiar? It should. It&#8217;s a picture of you in Dr. Hans Koehler&#8217;s medical file, complete with a list of every time he chiseled you or injected you, shaved you down or puffed you up.<br />
Klepper: I don&#8217;t recognize this person.<br />
Liz: Well, Koehler did a remarkable job of changing your appearance. But we both know that he can&#8217;t change your DNA. And that when we do take it, it&#8217;s gonna match up to his. Isn&#8217;t it, Doctor?<br />
Klepper: I like to make calculations.<br />
Liz: Like deciding who should live and who should die?<br />
Klepper: That&#8217;s one calculation, yes.<br />
Liz: Have you made it often?<br />
Klepper: Often enough. And it&#8217;s a surprisingly easy one. Others are considerably more difficult. Like why the FBI sent only one agent and one ‚Äì I&#8217;m not sure what.<br />
Lilly: We know who you were before Dr. Koehler changed your identity. What we want to know is who Raymond Reddington was.<br />
Liz: According to Koehler&#8217;s records, you and Reddington were patients at approximately the same time.<br />
Klepper: And you think, what, we bonded in post-op? Compared scars? [ CHUCKLES ] The whole point of going to Koehler was to become anonymous. I never saw him. He never saw me.<br />
[ CELLPHONE VIBRATING ] [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz steps out of the RV to take a call, leaving Lilly with the gun ]<br />
Liz: Whatcha got?<br />
Ressler: A guy at the RV park gave us a description of Klepper&#8217;s vehicle. Aram tracked it to a parking lot at 3rd and Sycamore.<br />
Liz: How far away are you?<br />
Ressler: About 10 minutes out.<br />
Liz: Lemme know what you find when you get there.<br />
Ressler: What about Reddington?<br />
Liz: Reddington?<br />
Ressler: Well, did you talk to him?<br />
Liz: Oh. Yeah. He didn&#8217;t know anything.<br />
Ressler: For once we know more than he does. All right, I&#8217;ll, uh, call you when we find something.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz goes back inside the RV ]<br />
Klepper: I have a gun. In that cupboard. On the top shelf.<br />
[ Liz opens the cupboard ]<br />
Liz: About Reddington If you didn&#8217;t see him, who did?<br />
Klepper: A nurse. She saw all the patients before and after. She could tell you who Reddington was.<br />
Liz: What&#8217;s her name?<br />
Klepper: Your colleagues are on their way. And for some reason, you didn&#8217;t tell them you were already here.<br />
Liz: What is her name?<br />
Klepper: I don&#8217;t randomly decide who&#8217;s gonna live or die. I do it based on whose life has more value. Take us, for example. I&#8217;m gonna spend the rest of my life in prison. You could have a long and productive career. By any reasonable standard, your life has more value, which is why you should get my gun.<br />
Liz: We need a name.<br />
Klepper: And I&#8217;ll give it to you once I get you to understand that you have to kill me.<br />
Liz: What are you talking about!?<br />
Klepper: I don&#8217;t know why you want to know who Reddington was, but clearly you&#8217;re willing to risk a great deal to find out. Your career, all the good and productive things you&#8217;ll do that makes your life more valuable than mine, but it only has that value if your colleagues never find out you were here. And the only way that&#8217;s gonna happen is if I&#8217;m dead when they arrive. Like I said, it&#8217;s a surprisingly easy calculation.<br />
Lilly: We&#8217;re not gonna kill you.<br />
Klepper: Of course not.<br />
Liz: [ Pause ] You&#8217;re gonna kill yourself. That&#8217;s what you do ‚Äì You stage killings and make them look like accidents.<br />
Klepper: Or suicides. My gun. You don&#8217;t have much time. Either I die here or I spend my life behind bars. In some ways, it&#8217;s a mercy killing.<br />
Lilly: [ To Liz ] You&#8217;re not actually considering ‚Äì<br />
Liz: Wait in the car.<br />
Lilly: You can&#8217;t do this.<br />
Klepper: The gun for the name. If she wants the name, she has no choice.<br />
Liz: Go.<br />
Lilly: This isn&#8217;t right.<br />
[ Lilly leaves. Liz picks up Klepper‚Äôs gun using a towel and places it on the table in front of him ]<br />
Klepper: Marguerite Renard. Find her, you&#8217;ll find out who Reddington was. It&#8217;s the ethical thing to do.<br />
[ Liz leaves the RV ] [ DOOR CREAKS ] [ DOOR THUDS SHUT ]<br />
[ BREATHING HEAVILY, Liz gets into the car with Lilly ] [ SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE ] We should go. [ ENGINE STARTS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Calexico‚Äôs ‚ô™ ‚ÄúWorld Undone‚Äù PLAYS ]<br />
[ Ressler, Samar and other agents arrive at the scene of Gerald Klepper‚Äôs suicide in the RV ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ You&#8217;re waiting for tenderness to come<br />

You can&#8217;t sleep for three days<br />
Now you&#8217;re waiting for tenderness to come<br />

[ Liz goes up to Ressler at the Post Office ]<br />
Liz: I heard about Klepper. He must&#8217;ve heard you were coming and decided killing himself was better than a life in prison. [ SIGHS ] Is that how you figure it?<br />
Ressler: Not exactly, no. I, uh found Klepper&#8217;s burner ‚Äì in the RV.</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ With a red bird on the branch
