<p>Ressler: That&#8217;s the number forensics pulled off it. And this is the number that you gave me. So, the way I &#8220;figure it,&#8221; is that you gave us a fake number so that we&#8217;d run in circles while you ran a trace on the real one so that you could get to Klepper first. See, first-thought theater was that you were doing it for Reddington. I mean, he&#8217;s not around, so you&#8217;re carrying his water for him.</p>

‚ô™ Now your world&#8217;s coming undone

<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Now your world&#8217;s coming undone
</p></blockquote>
<p>Ressler: ‚Äìany calls in or out.<br />
Liz: I can explain.<br />
Ressler: He doesn&#8217;t know anything about this case, does he? This is your Blacklister, not his.<br />
Liz: [ QUIETLY ] It&#8217;s a good explanation. I can&#8217;t tell you now, but I&#8217;ll tell you some day. For now, I just need you to trust me.<br />
Ressler: Did you kill Klepper?<br />
Liz: [ Insistently ] No. [ Pause ] But I did‚Äì let him kill himself.<br />
Ressler: Why?<br />
Liz: Because he convinced me the benefit outweighed the cost. The same way I&#8217;m trying to convince you not to tell Cooper what I&#8217;ve done.<br />
Ressler: [ SCOFFS ] Because the benefit outweighs the cost.<br />
Liz: [ SIGHS ] [ VOICE BREAKING ] I think so. That&#8217;s a decision you&#8217;re gonna have to make for yourself.<br />

‚ô™ Oo-oooo-oo-oooo-oo-oooo-oo-ummm<br />
Undone<br />

</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: Sir? Autopsy&#8217;s in on Klepper. All indications are it was a suicide.<br />
Cooper: We found evidence in Klepper&#8217;s RV that&#8217;d he&#8217;d made these sort of &#8220;ethical decisions&#8221; before. He killed 14 others. That we know of.<br />
Ressler: [ SIGHS LIGHTLY ]<br />
Cooper: You seem disappointed.<br />
Ressler: Doesn&#8217;t it bother you that&#8217;s there&#8217;s always an ulterior motive? Some reason we were given a case that&#8217;s never fully explained?<br />
Cooper: Not really, no. The way I look at it is, because of us, a serial killer is dead. No one will ever suffer because of him again. As far as I&#8217;m concerned, the case is closed. Unless there&#8217;s something I&#8217;m missing. Is there?<br />
Ressler: No, sir. It&#8217;s case closed.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz talks to Lilly on the phone ]<br />
Liz: Marguerite Renard. The nurse. We&#8217;ve got to find her.<br />
Lilly: Before he found you, could you have done it ‚Äì what you did in the RV?<br />
Liz: She can&#8217;t be hard to locate. And when we find her, we find out who Reddington really is.<br />
Lilly: Could you have done it?<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t think so. No.<br />
Lilly: So he did this to you.<br />
Liz: What difference does it make? We&#8217;re so close!<br />
Lilly: The difference that it makes is that I&#8217;m worried that he&#8217;s gonna do it to me.<br />
Liz: That won&#8217;t happen. It won&#8217;t.<br />
[ Lilly picks up a pen to write ]<br />
Lilly: Okay. Marguerite Renard. What do we know about her? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Federal Medical Center, Dr Grey‚Äôs Office ]<br />
Dr Grey: Your friend, Mr. Rodrick. He&#8217;s why you&#8217;re here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Please tell me you&#8217;re going to be administering the Szondi test. I&#8217;m absolutely fascinated by repressed impulses.<br />
Dr Grey: There will be no more tests, Mr. Reddington. Our work is finished here.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That seems premature.<br />
Dr Grey: I saw all I needed to see today with your friend, Mr. Rodrick.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You keep calling him my friend. He&#8217;s not my friend.<br />
Dr Grey: Well, whoever he is, he was intent on killing me. I think he said he was going to, uh, &#8220;rip my tongue out.&#8221; But your reaction was everything.<br />
<b>Red:</b> My reaction?<br />
Dr Grey: You came to my defense. You saw that Mr. Rodrick was intent on causing me harm, and although you don&#8217;t know me, you made the very conscious decision to stop him, which, to my mind, is a ‚Äì is a wonderful demonstration of your ability to distinguish between right and wrong.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m not so sure of that.<br />
Dr Grey: Yeah, but you&#8217;re not the doctor. Before I submit my decision, I have one more question.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m an open book.<br />
Dr Grey: What exactly is it you want from Mr. Rodrick? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The courtroom in the SDNY ]<br />
Judge Roberta Wilkins: I have reviewed the results of the psychiatric evaluation conducted at the defendant&#8217;s request, and it is Dr. Grey&#8217;s professional opinion that, while one with a criminal history like Mr. Reddington would likely have to be insane, it&#8217;s clear his criminal proclivities do not rise to the level of legal insanity. It is the doctor&#8217;s professional opinion that the defendant does understand the charges leveled against him and is, therefore, fully mentally competent to assist in his own defense. Mr. Reddington, you&#8217;ve been provided with a copy of Dr. Grey&#8217;s findings.<br />
[ Red waves his copy ]<br />
Judge Wilkins: Are you objecting to her conclusions?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, Your Honor. I&#8217;m prepared to accept the finding of competency.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Wonderful. Then we&#8217;re clear to proceed. Mr. Sima?<br />
Asst US Atty Sima: Your Honor, of the indictments that are before the court, the prosecution has elected to proceed with the charge of treason as our first case against the defendant.<br />
Judge Wilkins: Very well. We&#8217;ll move to jury selection immediately.<br />
[ GAVEL BANGS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ It‚Äôs lockup time at Colton Prison. Red is back in his cell with the messenger-rat system between himself and Dembe ]<br />
[ DOOR CREAKING, THUDS SHUT ] [ KEYS JINGLE, LOCK ENGAGES ] [ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ] [ LOCK DISENGAGES ] [ DOOR CREAKS OPEN ]<br />
[ Red pulls the string that runs through the broken pipe into his cell. He pulls out a burner phone wrapped in plastic ] [ PLASTIC RIPS ] [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] [ LINE RINGING ] [ CELLPHONE RINGS, BEEPS ]<br />
Dembe: You got the phone.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, thank you, and not a moment too soon.<br />
Dembe: Why? What&#8217;s wrong?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I spoke with Atticus Rodrick.<br />
Dembe: Was he any help?<br />
<b>Red:</b> He gave me a name ‚Äì General Shiro. I need you to find out everything you can about him.<br />
Dembe: General Shiro?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. He&#8217;s the next name on the Blacklist.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:7 General Shiro (‚Ññ 116)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red convinced the judge for his upcoming trial for treason to send him to a federal medical center for a psychiatric evaluation. His hidden purpose was to connect with Atticus Rodrick. When he got there, he found that Atticus was under heavy sedation, so he substituted Skittles for Atticus‚Äôs meds. Off his meds, Atticus attacked the psychiatrist and Red instinctively intervened, which convinced the psychiatrist that Red could indeed tell right from wrong. However, she also discerned that Red was an ‚Äúimposter‚Äù: </p>
<blockquote><p>

Judge Wilkins: With the jury in place, trial is set to commence Tuesday morning at 8:00 a.m. I will see you all then.<br />
[ Red and Sima rise to leave ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s a smug little grin.<br />
Sima: I&#8217;ve been a prosecutor for 18 years. I have empaneled over 300 juries. It&#8217;s usually a flip of a coin as to which way they&#8217;re gonna lean, but this group This is a two-headed coin, my friend. Your fate is sealed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;ll see about that.<br />
Sima: I respect the false confidence, but you and I both know ‚Äì you&#8217;re a dead man walking.</p>

<h3>Episode Songs</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>‚ô´ Mongolian Throat Singing No. 7</b><br />
By Erdem Baatar</p>
<div style="line-height:1.2em;">
<span style="font-size:x-small;">‚ô™ [ Vocalization only ] Wikipedia: <b>Tuvan throat singing, Khoomei, Hooliin Chor (in Mongolian, ‚Äòthroat harmony‚Äô), or Mongolian throat singing</b> is one particular variant of overtone singing practiced by people in Mongolia, Inner Mongolia, Tuva and Siberia. In 2009, it was inscribed on the Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity of UNESCO, under the name Mongolian art of singing, Khoomei. </span> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:x-small;">In Mongolian throat singing, the performer produces a fundamental pitch and‚Äîsimultaneously‚Äîone or more pitches over that. The history of Mongolian throat singing reaches far back. Many male herders can throat sing, but women are beginning to practice the technique as well. The popularity of throat singing among Mongolians seems to have arisen as a result of geographic location and culture. The open landscape of Mongolia allows for the sounds to carry a great distance. Ethnomusicologists studying throat singing in these areas mark khoomei as an integral part in the ancient pastoral animism that is still practiced today. ‚Ä¶ </span></div>
<p>Lyrics and Credits: [ None ] Wikipedia: <a href="http://bit.ly/2Ndz5z6" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/2Ndz5z6</a><br />
YouTube: <a href="https://youtu.be/NWXBnAw9D-k" rel="nofollow">https://youtu.be/NWXBnAw9D-k</a>
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:8 Marko Jankowics (‚Ññ 58)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red has come up short in his attempt to plant a sympathetic juror on the jury and his trial for treason is set to begin. In a final gambit to secure a ‚Äúget-out-of-jail-free‚Äù card, Red has had Dembe go to the files of the last Blacklister (#116 General Shiro) to get the address of a person Red is sure must have been sent some of General Shiro‚Äôs deadly ‚Äúbug juice‚Äù (deadly genetically-altered beetles, eggs or larvae). </p>
<p>Meanwhile, Liz and Lilly/Jennifer‚Äôs next step in their search to find out Red‚Äôs true identity is clear: to locate the woman, Marguerite Renard, who was the nurse of plastic surgeon Dr Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33) around the time he changed Red‚Äôs appearance to assume the identity of their father, the real Raymond Reddington. Liz got the name of the nurse from Gerald Todd Klepper (Blacklister #91 The Ethicist) in exchange for letting him commit suicide. Ressler wised up to the fact Liz had done an end-run around the Task Force and confronted her about Klepper‚Äôs death. Liz begged Ressler not to tell Cooper but to ‚Äútrust‚Äù her that ‚Äúthe benefit outweigh[ed] the cost.‚Äù (So far, the Task Force is in the dark about the fact that Liz and Lilly found out that Red isn‚Äôt the real Raymond Reddington.)</p>
<p>Dembe‚Äôs centrality to the mystery of Red‚Äôs identity came into sharper focus in a tale Red told to Cooper about how Dembe saved his life when a trawler capsized in a typhoon in the Philippines. (‚ÄúDembe saved my life that night. Dembe&#8217;s always saved my life.‚Äù) Also, Liz was surprised to learn that Dembe remembers her mother: </p>
<blockquote><p>
Liz: He [Red] said I reminded him of my mother. ‚Ä¶<br />
Dembe: He&#8217;s right. You remind me of her, too.<br />
Liz: You know everything. Don&#8217;t you? Everything about him. All the answers I&#8217;m looking for.<br />
Dembe: I do.
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:9 Minister D (‚Ññ 99)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Liz and Lilly (Jennifer), determined to find Marguerite Renard, the nurse for Dr Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33) at the time Red‚Äôs identity was changed to that of Raymond Reddington, discovered more than they were looking for. They stumbled into an LSD-trafficking ring run by Marko Jankowics (Blacklister #58). Jankowics used young women as drug mules by having large quantities of the drug sewn into their abdomens, thus mimicing pregnancy. In a fudged attempt to abduct Marguerite, the drug ring took Lilly captive instead. Though beaten mercilessly by Jankowics, Lilly was able to find out from Marguerite that although she did not know Red‚Äôs true identity, that his surgery had been set up by a Russian woman, very likely Katarina Rostova.</p>
<p>Liz turned to Red for help finding Jankowics in order to save Jennifer. In the process of asking inmates in Colton Prison (where he is still awaiting trial), Red too found that out that Jankowics‚Äôs girlfriend was Marguerite Renard, so now Red knows for certain that Liz is trying to find out about his past. In order to save Lilly, Liz also turned to Ressler and confided in him the fact that Red is not the real Raymond Reddington, but an imposter. Ressler and Liz were able to rescue Lilly on a tip from Red and take out the drug dealers, but Dembe, at Red‚Äôs direction, got to Marguerite before she could spill any more beans and, one way or another, Marguerite is unlikely to be heard from again.</p>
<p>After being rescued, a nerve-wracked Lilly decided she had had enough of the wild life and headed off for a quieter existence on Long Island, leaving Liz and her new co-conspirator Ressler to continue to pursue the secrets of Red‚Äôs past. Oh. Did I mention that Red ended a gang war inside the prison? There‚Äôs also that.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In a room lined with shelf upon shelf of archived audio tapes, a man works a complex array of 1980s-era recording equipment, including a switchboard, moving tape drives and a manual typewriter. The man has a deep, irregular scar on his left cheek. He moves quickly between recorded conversations ]</p>
<blockquote><p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz visits Red in his holding cell ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> Someone close. Traitors always are.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
LIz: According to Reddington, Minister D gathers incriminating information and then uses it to extort people. In 2004, he discovered an insider trading scheme and used the information to extort $4 million from a pair of traders at Koji Analytics. Six years ago, he blackmailed Senator Constance Holsted after finding proof of a kickback scheme between the senator&#8217;s husband and a major real estate developer.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>‚ãò‚ãô<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ A delivery man enters an office and hands an envelope to a secretary ]<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Ressler: Our interest is Minister D. If you help us, we&#8217;ll look past your little indiscretions.<br />
[ CHAIR CREAKING ]<br />
Shah: I came to my office one day after lunch, and there was this envelope.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Ressler: I was. Yes. The U.S.S. Gideon was an Ohio-class submarine sunk by the Soviet Navy while on a secret mission in the Barents Sea. 134 men were on board. They all died.<br />
Sima: You say it was a secret mission. How did the Soviet Navy find out about it?<br />
Ressler: Because Raymond Reddington told them.<br />
Sima: Was the defendant the only one who knew about the mission?<br />

Sima: If 16 people were aware of the mission, how can you be sure the defendant was the informant?<br />
Ressler: Two days before the sub was attacked, the Gideon&#8217;s captain changed course to avoid weather. The change was communicated to an intelligence officer who was assigned to the mission. He was the only one of the 16 who knew the coordinates of the sub on the day in question.<br />
Sima: Who was that intelligence officer?<br />
Ressler: Raymond Reddington.<br />
Sima: So, the defendant was the only one who knew the location of the submarine. That doesn&#8217;t prove he told the Russians how to find it. Why are you so certain that he did?<br />

Ressler: It is.<br />

[ The Courtroom ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> 35 years ago, a Naval intelligence officer working for the U.S. government fell‚Äî fell into a relationship with a beautiful Russian woman. Unbeknownst to his superiors, that relationship, which started as guarded attraction, quickly evolved into passion, which resulted in pregnancy.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;They had the child. A girl, whom they both loved.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;What the Naval officer didn&#8217;t know, but certainly should have suspected, was that the Russian woman was a KGB officer that Katarina Rostova had been assigned to get close to Raymond Reddington and steal classified information from him.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;What Reddington could never have suspected was that though she was a KGB agent, Rostova&#8217;s real handlers were members of a secret criminal organization, a multinational cabal working in the shadows to manipulate world governments, economic markets, trade, and international alliances.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;When Reddington discovered this, he confronted Rostova, who warned him that if he threatened to expose them, the Cabal would destroy his reputation, discrediting him so he could not discredit them.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;And that&#8217;s what happened. With the help of the Cabal, Rostova framed Reddington with the very evidence you&#8217;ve heard in this courtroom. To prevent him from protecting his country, she made it appear as if he had betrayed it.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;As a result, the Cabal remained in the shadows, Rostova disappeared, and Raymond Reddington became a completely different person. A man who has done many brutal, scary, illegal things, but not a single one ‚Äì ever ‚Äì that was treasonous.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s it every box, file, and tape.<br />
Liz: We must have missed something.<br />
Cooper: Or it&#8217;s not here.<br />
Liz: We have to start over.<br />
[ Samar accidentally knocks the framed photo from the table ] [ CLATTERS, GLASS SHATTERS ‚ö°Ô∏è]<br />
Aram: I think it&#8217;s too late for that.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s gotta be here somewhere.It has to be.<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;ll start over.<br />
[ Samar picks up the shattered photo. The paper backing has ripped open. inside is a mini-audio tape labeled ‚ÄúK. R. Dec 7, 1990‚Äù ]<br />
Samar: Uh, I don&#8217;t think we have to. December 7, 1990.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The courtroom ]<br />
Sima: Let me just get this straight ‚Äì You were framed by a &#8220;secret criminal organization&#8221;?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry. I misspoke. Thanks to me, the Cabal is no longer secret.<br />

[ Ressler enter, makes eye contact with Red ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> Yes. Though, for the life of me, I don&#8217;t understand what the rush is all about. Everyone seems so anxious to kill me. Makes you wonder. [ To Judge Wilkins ] Perhaps you could enlighten me over a cocktail after my acquittal which is inevitable now that the evidence has arrived.<br />
Sima: Permission to approach?<br />

Sima: Whatever evidence his FBI lackey just stepped and fetched for him‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s a tape recording.<br />
Sima: That we haven&#8217;t had the chance to authenticate.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Then let&#8217;s get Agent Ressler to hop on the stand, cross his heart, hope to die, and do just that.<br />
Judge Wilkins: I agree. Mr. Sima, you will have the chance to cross-examine the witness and authenticate the tape. Mr. Reddington, it appears that all your eggs are in this basket. You better hope they don&#8217;t crack.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mm. [ To Sima ] That loud whooshing sound is the wind blowing out of your case.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

[ CLICKS ] </p>
<blockquote><p>

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:10 The Cryptobanker (‚Ññ 160)</h2>

Program air date: 3/8/2019 in the US<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:10 The Cryptobanker (‚Ññ 160)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): The jury is in. Liz‚Äôs father Raymond Reddington was not a traitor to the United States but rather was framed by Liz‚Äôs mother, Katarina Rostova, when he found out that, not only was she a KGB officer who had been sent to seduce him, but that her true handlers belonged to the Cabal. To discredit him, she planted a communiqu√© for US intelligence to discover blaming Reddington for the sinking of a US submarine which resulted in the deaths of over 100 men in 1990. Red‚Äôs acquittal was secured when the Task Force retrieved from the archives of Jordan Loving (Minister D, Blacklister #99), a tape recording between Katarina and Cabal leader Alan Fitch describing the plot. </p>
<p>Of course, the ‚ÄúRed‚Äù who was on trial is not the real ‚ÄúRaymond Reddington,‚Äù as Liz had recently told Ressler who was called as a witness at the trial. He perjured himself by identifying Red as Raymond Reddington while under oath. But he hesitated, raising suspicions in Red‚Äôs mind about just what Ressler knows.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Dembe got hold of the recording of the 911 call that resulted in Red‚Äôs arrest. A homeless woman made the call for $100. When she could not identify Liz from a photo as the person who asked her to make the call, Dembe figured out it must have been Jennifer working with Liz. He confronted Liz and she begged him not to tell Red, which he did not do when meeting with Red later.</p>
<p>Though acquitted of treason, Red remains behind bars on other charges. His next ploy to earn his freedom began by obtaining the target list from the files of General Shiro (Blacklister #116) which provided an address in London from which Dembe returned with photocopies of files.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Matt Pierson watches his daughter Jamie play soccer. At the same time he talks business on his cell phone ] [ INDISTINCT SHOUTING ] [ CROWD CHEERING ]<br />
Matt Pierson: [ To Jamie ] Yes! ‚Äì Way to go, Jamie!<br />
Jamie: Thanks, Dad!<br />
Pierson: No, yeah, I&#8217;m open to the idea of a different distributor, but not increasing the specs for the batteries themselves. [ BEEPING ] Oh, hold on. I&#8217;m getting another call. [ BEEPS ] Hey, this is Matt.<br />
Oleg Gromov: [ Heavy Russian accent ] Hello, Matt. I need you to listen. What I am about to tell you is very important.<br />
Pierson: [ SCOFFS ] Is this a‚Äì Who is this?<br />
Gromov: First, I need you to understand the degree of control I have. Keep your eyes on your daughter. You and I both understand she is vulnerable. I have the ability to exploit that fact.<br />
Pierson: Jamie.<br />
Jamie: Aah! [ GROANING ]<br />
[ Jamie collapses, clutching her heart ]<br />
Pierson: Jamie!<br />
[ Pierson runs to Jamie‚Äôs side ]<br />
Coach: Girls, take a knee.<br />
Pierson: What&#8217;s wrong? Honey, talk to me.<br />
Gromov: It&#8217;s quite simple, Matt. I&#8217;ve taken control of your daughter&#8217;s pacemaker and instructed her SA node to trigger a 3rd degree AV block. Her heart&#8217;s electrical signals have turned off.<br />
Pierson: Please, stop. Why are you doing this?<br />
Gromov: Quiet, Matt. Now I&#8217;m going to give you some very specific instructions. I want you to do exactly as I say. Are you ready, Matt?<br />
Pierson: Yes.<br />
Gromov: You are going to liquidate a few assets for me. Start with your Union Bank pension and your shares in the company stock. Do you hear me?<br />
Pierson: Yes, Union Bank, company stock. Just, please, I&#8217;m begging you, stop.<br />
Gromov: Please don&#8217;t tell anyone we spoke, Matt. Talk to the authorities and Jamie pays the price. I will be in touch. Until then, your daughter can have her heart back.<br />
Jamie: [ INHALES DEEPLY ]<br />
Coach: Is she okay?<br />
Woman: Do you want some water?<br />
Woman #2: Way to go, honey.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Gromov sits in a darkened room with computer monitors on all sides ]<br />
[ HEADSET CLATTERS ] [ DIALING ]<br />
Gromov: I&#8217;m into a new deal. It&#8217;s huge. After this, I&#8217;m buying an island.<br />
Cryptobanker: When should I anticipate the transfer?<br />
Gromov: End of day tomorrow. We&#8217;re talking $3 million. Can you handle that?<br />
Cryptobanker: It&#8217;s complicated, but it&#8217;s viable. Contact me when you&#8217;ve got the crypto.<br />
[ CELLPHONE CLICKS ]<br />
Gromov: Yes! Whoo! </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Outside Colton Prison BIRD CAWS ]<br />

<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:11 Bastien Moreau (‚Ññ 20)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red‚Äôs life is on the line. Red pleaded guilty to a large number of crimes after the prosecutor was about to make public to the jury the fact that Red has for five years had an Immunity Agreement with the government. Not only would that endanger Red‚Äôs life, but the lives of all those on the Task Force. So he pleaded guilty in order to protect them. The jury was instructed only to consider his punishment. Their determination: death by lethal injection. </p>
<p>Red did attempt a prison break, but it was scuttled. His only hope now lies in revealing a conspiracy whose consequences would be so dire that he believes his life could be spared and he would be freed with his Immunity Agreement intact. The next step is for Liz to get from The Cryptobanker (Blacklister #160), who is now under arrest, the location of a ‚Äúman in Cairo‚Äù to whom the Cryptobanker had sent laundered funds. The information that such a transaction took place was obtained by Dembe from a London apartment based on the tracking list of General Shiro (Blacklister #116), the radical scientist who created weaponized insects. So far, The Cryptobanker has not cooperated. </p>
<p>As for Liz‚Äôs quest to find out Red‚Äôs true identity and understand why he assumed the identity of her father the real Raymond Reddington: In addition to Liz and Lilly/Jennifer, Ressler now also knows that Red is an imposter. The narrative told by Red at his treason trial revealed that Raymond Reddington was not a traitor but rather was framed by Liz‚Äôs mother Katarina Rostova, a KGB agent and member of the Cabal. Ressler wonders why Red would take on the identity of a man known at the time only as a pariah. Dembe knows Liz (and Lilly/Jennifer) arranged for a homeless woman to make the call that led to Red‚Äôs capture which they hoped would give them the space to find out about Red‚Äôs past. Dembe confronted Liz, but following her pleas, has not so far shared this information with Red. Lilly/Jennifer, after being brutally beaten by Marko Jankowics (Blacklister #58), retreated to Long Island. Cooper, Samar and Aram remain in the dark.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ DOOR OPENS ] [ Bastien Moreau enters a darkened room ]<br />
Bastien Moreau: [ On phone ] When you contract with me, ‚Äì there are certain implied assurances.<br />
[ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
Moreau: Things may take longer than you like. We might hit a few bumps along the way, but in the end, the job will be done in such a way that it never comes back on you or your people.<br />
Anna McMahon: Yes, well, the job is not done.<br />
Moreau: It will be.<br />
McMahon: You said that before. This should&#8217;ve been done weeks ago.<br />
Moreau: As I said before, you should expect a few bumps along the way‚Äì<br />
McMahon: I&#8217;m not interested in bumps. I only want results, ‚Äì which you have yet to show me.<br />
[ SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE ] Because of you, because that bombing at the UN was stopped by the FBI, we&#8217;re now in crisis mode. We need this done. Finish the job ‚Äì both of them ‚Äì or my people will take this into their own hands, and you don&#8217;t want that.<br />
Moreau: [ LAUGHING ] Oh. A sense of humor. I like that about you.<br />
McMahon: Can you get it done or not?<br />
Moreau: Tell your boss to relax. They will both be dead within two days.<br />
McMahon: I&#8217;m on my way to see him now. I&#8217;ll tell him. Just get it done.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
[ Anna McMahon gets out of a chauffeured vehicle ‚Äì at the White House]<br />
[ SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE ]<br />
McMahon: [ To Security ] The President&#8217;s expecting me.<br />
[ WAILING CONTINUES ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram/Samar‚Äôs place ] [ Aram is in the kitchen. The tv is on ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
[ A group of people with signs protest the death penalty ] [ INDISTINCT SHOUTING ]<br />

After being on the FBI&#8217;s watch list‚Äì
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Aram is so distracted by the coverage he spills coffee on his hand ‚Äì and on a cell phone ]<br />
Aram: Ouch! Ow! ‚Äì </p>
<blockquote><p>
Anchor: ‚Äìfor decades Reddington was‚Äì
</p></blockquote>
<p>Samar: [ At a distance ] Are you okay?<br />
Aram: Uh, yeah. Uh, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah. Uh, fine, fine, fine. All- All good.</p>
<blockquote><p>
Anchor: ‚Äìpleaded guilty to 16 other counts that‚Äì
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ TV SHUTS OFF, REMOTE THUMPS ]<br />
Aram: Um. Why do they always execute people at 12:01? ‚Äì It&#8217;s so ghoulish.<br />
[ Aram wipes the phone ] [ CELLPHONE CHIMES ] [ A text message on the phone reads: ‚ÄúThis is Dan with NAA. Found speech pathologist for impairment therapy. When can you start?‚Äù ]<br />
Samar: The death warrant is only good for one day.<br />
[ Samar enters. Aram finishes wiping off the phone and places it back on the counter ]<br />

Aram: Appeals? ‚Äì<br />
Samar: Yes, appeals. They can deal with them and get the execution done without needing another warrant.<br />
[ COFFEE POURING ]<br />
Aram: So it&#8217;s not ghoulish. It&#8217;s, uh, calculated. That&#8217;s worse.<br />
[ COFFEE POT THUMPS LIGHTLY ]<br />
Samar: Are you sure you&#8217;re okay?<br />
Aram: To be honest? Uh, no. I&#8217;m not.<br />
Samar: It&#8217;s a dumb question. Nobody is today. [ SIGHS ] I can&#8217;t believe he&#8217;s going to die. He always seemed so invincible.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Federal Penitentiary in Terre Haute, Indiana ]<br />
[ Red and Cooper, separated by a window, talk to one another on telephones ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you for coming, Harold.<br />
Cooper: How are you holding up, my friend?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll know in a few hours. They&#8217;re giving me a physical to make sure I&#8217;m healthy enough to be killed.<br />

<b>Red:</b> He won&#8217;t.<br />
Cooper: I hope you&#8217;re wrong. It&#8217;s the only card we have to play.<br />
<b>Red:</b> For now.<br />

<b>Red:</b> Well, it&#8217;s scheduled for then. But it won&#8217;t happen if you do exactly as I suggest.<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;ll do whatever it takes.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Good. Because it&#8217;s gonna require you to steal account information from a bank in Luxembourg.<br />

<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHING ] Don&#8217;t look so sour. At this time of year, the valleys of the Black Ernz are just beautiful. Elizabeth will tell you the why. You&#8217;ll have to figure out the how or this will be goodbye.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ KNOCK AT DOOR ] [ Jonas Kruger enters Bastien Moreau‚Äôs room ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Liz: That&#8217;s what we have to find out.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Jonas Kruger: Everything you will need. Her schedule, her security detail, and my I.D., which gives you access.<br />
[ Jonas notices a cylindrical blue container in a briefcase ]<br />
Kruger: What is that?<br />
Bastien Moreau: Thanks for your business.<br />
Kruger: [ WHISPERING ] $5 million to betray my country.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: Reddington has uncovered a conspiracy. He doesn&#8217;t know its purpose or who&#8217;s involved except for a &#8220;man in Cairo&#8221; he can&#8217;t find. Now his salvation lies in a numbered account in a bank we have no authority to access, but which he wants us to rob.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Moreau: Our work together is finished.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: Is that it?<br />
Liz: Except for the fact that we&#8217;re not asking for your help.<br />
Cooper: We?<br />
Liz: Me and Dembe.<br />
Cooper: This is not your call to make.<br />
Liz: There&#8217;s no time to plan and little hope for success. It&#8217;s a mission that will likely end in our arrest. That&#8217;s a chance we&#8217;re willing to take. We don&#8217;t expect anyone else to take it.<br />
Cooper: They would if you asked them.<br />
Liz: I know. That&#8217;s why I&#8217;m not going to ask them.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office open area. Aram walks up to Samar ]<br />
Aram: Hey, uh I, uh I spilled, uh, coffee this morning. Uh, I was, um, watching the news about Mr. Reddington and, um, uh, point being, I spilled on your phone.<br />
Samar: It&#8217;s okay. It works fine.<br />
Aram: Yeah, I know. Because, uh, while I was cleaning it, you got a text. About seeing a speech pathologist.<br />
Samar. Can we talk about this later?<br />
Aram: Uh, the text was from the National Aphasia Association. Uh, it said NAA, but, uh, then I looked it up.<br />
Samar: Aram, I don&#8217;t want to talk about this here.<br />
Aram: And then I looked up &#8220;aphasia.&#8221; Samar, I am confused and worried, and- and I&#8217;m a little annoyed that you didn&#8217;t say anything. So, no, I don&#8217;t think we can talk about this later. I think it&#8217;s been long enough.<br />
[ TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE ]<br />
Samar: When I was stuck in the car I was under water for six minutes. Being deprived of oxygen for that long‚Äì by the time you pulled me out, the damage was already done.<br />
Aram: What damage? The migraines?<br />
Samar: Yes, but there&#8217;s more than that. I can&#8217;t remember things. Numbers, um, prepositions.<br />
Aram: Words. Like &#8220;appeals.&#8221;<br />
Samar: Uh. Sometimes there&#8217;s a blinding light, and I can&#8217;t do anything. I thought it would get better. But now I know that it won&#8217;t.<br />
Aram: But you&#8217;re seeing a therapist.<br />
Samar: Yes. But not to improve. To manage the decline.<br />
Aram: W-What can I do? Uh, tell me. Tell me what to do, I&#8217;ll do it.<br />
Samar: I know, but there&#8217;s nothing anyone can do.<br />
[ FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING ] [ It‚Äôs Ressler ]<br />
Ressler: Did Cooper go see Reddington?<br />
Samar: He went. I don&#8217;t know if he saw him. The minute he came in, he pulled Liz into his office.<br />
[ TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE ]<br />
[ Liz comes down the yellow stairs from Cooper‚Äôs office and walks quickly toward elevator. Aram starts to go after her ]<br />
Ressler: Don&#8217;t.<br />
Aram: What? She shouldn&#8217;t be alone.<br />
[ ELEVATOR DOOR OPENS ]<br />

[ ELEVATOR DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
[ Cooper walks up ]<br />

Cooper: As a matter of fact, he hasn&#8217;t.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A private aviation airport ] [ ENGINES RUMBLING SOFTLY ]<br />

[ Liz enters along with the Warden ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth!<br />
[ RADIO CHATTER ]<br />
Warden: Your food is almost ready.<br />
[ A guard removes Red‚Äôs handcuffs ] [ HANDCUFFS CLICKING ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Excellent! Make it a table for two.<br />
[ DOOR SLIDES closed ]<br />
Liz: What you said about Ziegler ‚Äì we were able to corroborate it. We can prove the conspiracy&#8217;s real.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;re going to be phenomenally wealthy.<br />
Liz: Panabaker got Cooper another meeting with the President. He&#8217;s gonna make the argument that, in order to save her life, the President has to save yours.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;ll be able to live anywhere you want. You&#8217;ll be able to do anything you want.<br />
Liz: What I want to do is save your life.<br />
[ DOOR SLIDES OPEN ]<br />
Guard: All right, time to eat.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ah, my final meal. I can&#8217;t think of anyone I&#8217;d rather share it with.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m trying to tell you ‚Äì this might not be your final meal.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And I&#8217;m trying to tell you I&#8217;m okay if it is. [ BREATHES DEEPLY ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING over DC ] [ SIRENS WAILING ]<br />
[ Ressler and Samar arrive at the hotel ]<br />
Ressler: Agent Ressler, FBI. We believe we&#8217;re looking for an explosive device. Possibly biological. Now, suspect had access to your advance team, so the device is likely inside your secure cordon.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Lead BND Agent: Ma&#8217;am, the Senator is here, but it sounds like we may have a security concern.<br />
Ava Ziegler: What concerns?<br />
Lead BND Agent: We&#8217;re waiting on details.<br />
Ziegler: Let me know the minute you know more.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: Yeah. Aram, can you pull Navabi&#8217;s reports from the UN bombing and see what kind of details we have on that device?<br />
Aram: Are you looking for schematics?<br />
Ressler: No, I&#8217;m looking for any details that can tell us what we&#8217;re searching for. Anything you can send the Bomb Unit is helpful.<br />
Aram: Okay, understood. I&#8217;m on it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: This is what you call a last meal?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ]<br />
Liz: Cabbage soup and herring.<br />
<b>Red:</b> My mother made it for me when I was a child.<br />
Liz: I can&#8217;t imagine that. You as a boy.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I was a difficult child. People saw me one way ‚Äì I saw myself another. I felt misunderstood ‚Äì acted out. My father fancied himself a disciplinarian. Very moralistic. Instead of trying to understand me, he excommunicated me.<br />
Liz: And your mother?<br />
<b>Red:</b> My mother- My m- My mother- My mother understood.<br />
Liz: About who you used to be ‚Äì there&#8217;s something I need to ask you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> My mother understood the problems of the human heart in conflict with itself. So she understood Everything. I&#8217;ve taught you to think like a criminal. I should&#8217;ve taught you to think like her. I-I should&#8217;ve learned to think like her. All those years spent worrying about you ‚Äì fancying myself your guardian angel. She would&#8217;ve taken one look at you and known you&#8217;d be fine. And not because of the money I obsessively cobbled together for you but because you have in your life the only thing that matters ‚Äì people who love you ‚Äì<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: Harold Cooper to see the President.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> ‚Äì people you can depend on ‚Äì people who will always tell you the truth. Six years ago, I turned myself in because of you. Now, here, at the end, I&#8217;m at peace because of them.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ava Ziegler: Senator Wade, thank you for agreeing to meet.<br />
Senator Wade: Of course. Please.<br />
[ They sit ]<br />
Senator Wade: Now, you said it was urgent. Is something wrong?<br />
Ziegler: Our intelligence network has been working cooperatively with a former MI6 agent. Earlier today, he showed me a dossier outlining a plot against America.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Bastien Moreau wheels a room service cart to a hotel room and knocks ] [ KNOCKS AT DOOR ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Karl Hartmans enters Ziegler‚Äôs suite with Ressler ]<br />
Karl Hartmans: Madam Ziegler, I&#8217;m terribly sorry ‚Äì<br />
Ziegler: Karl, what&#8217;s going on?<br />
Ressler: Ma&#8217;am, we have a security issue. You need to come with me. We need to get you and the Senator out of this building right now.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Christopher Miles opens his hotel room door ] [ DOOR CREAKS ]<br />
Miles: Ah. I, uh, didn&#8217;t order room service.<br />
Bastien Moreau: You have a dossier I&#8217;m interested in.<br />
[ GUN COCKS ] [ Door closes ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The White House ]<br />
Cooper: Ms. McMahon thought Reddington was lying to save his life. Now we know he was telling the truth.<br />
Anna McMahon: So he was telling the truth. It doesn&#8217;t undo all the horrible things he&#8217;s done.<br />
Cooper: This isn&#8217;t about what he&#8217;s done. I thought I&#8217;d made that clear. This is about what he&#8217;s going to do save Ava Ziegler&#8217;s life.<br />
President Diaz: I thought that your job.<br />
Panabaker: His job is to try to stop it. And he&#8217;s doing everything he can, but in our experience, if Reddington says he&#8217;s the only one who can solve it, he&#8217;s the only one who can solve it.<br />
McMahon: For God&#8217;s sakes, the FBI employs 35,000 people. He&#8217;s one man.<br />
Cooper: Mr. President, it&#8217;s simple. You can listen to Ms. McMahon, and a prominent German official will die, or you can listen to me, and she&#8217;ll survive.<br />
[ CELLPHONE RINGING ]<br />
Cooper: May I?<br />
Diaz: Please.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Diaz: You&#8217;ve already given me plenty to think about.<br />
Cooper: When? You&#8217;re sure about this? No, no. No, I&#8217;m relieved. Good work.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Panabaker: Harold?<br />
Cooper: Our people have Ziegler in custody. They&#8217;re off-site. She&#8217;s safe.<br />
McMahon: Well, what do you know ‚Äì looks like you didn&#8217;t need Reddington&#8217;s help after all.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> You wanted to ask me something.<br />
Liz: I did. [ Smiles ] I wanted to ask you ‚Äì I-I wanted to ask [ Pause ] how can you eat that?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHING ] It&#8217;s terrible, isn&#8217;t it?<br />
Liz: I mean, honestly, it&#8217;s the worst food I&#8217;ve ever seen. Your mother may have been a wonderful person, but she was a terrible cook.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHING ] You&#8217;re right. Everything we had growing up was either over-boiled or under-cured.<br />
Liz: This can&#8217;t be your last meal. It&#8217;s the definition of cruel and unusual.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ]<br />
[ DOOR SLIDES OPEN ]<br />
Warden: It&#8217;s time. Once you&#8217;ve changed, we&#8217;ll move into the execution chamber.<br />
[ CELLPHONE VIBRATING ]<br />
[ DOOR SLIDES SHUT ]<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s Cooper. [ QUIETLY ] Have you seen the President? But she&#8217;s in danger. She&#8217;s not safe.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Let it go.<br />
Liz: I know it seems that way, but you and I both know this isn&#8217;t over.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth, let it go.<br />
Liz: The President&#8217;s wrong!<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s too late for Ziegler. You&#8217;ll need to focus on the larger conspiracy.<br />
Liz: Thank you for trying. Of course. I&#8217;ll tell him.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Liz: [ VOICE BREAKING ] He says he wishes there was more that he could do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He did everything he could. That&#8217;s- That&#8217;s more than enough for me. I should change.<br />
Liz: I love you. [ QUIETLY ] That&#8217;s what I wanted to say. That&#8217;s what I wanted you to hear.<br />
[ Red stares at her, shocked ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The kitchen of a restaurant or hotel ]<br />
Samar: We&#8217;ve got the principal in a off-site holding location. 8323 14th Street Northwest.<br />
Aram: Copy that. 8323 14th Street Northwest. I have a DC PD escort en route. Awaiting instructions from BND and DSS. [ Diplomatic Security Service ]<br />
Ressler: You&#8217;re in charge? We need you to get everybody out of here. Now.<br />
Ana Ziegler: [ COUGHS ]<br />
BND Agent: Ma&#8217;am, are you okay?<br />
Ziegler: [ SNIFFLES ] I- I can&#8217;t catch my breath.<br />
BND Agent: You&#8217;re gonna be okay. We have a BND convoy on the way. We want you in the air in the next 20 minutes.<br />
Ressler: You. Lock it down. All entrances. I want DC PD units on the alley. The minute the escort&#8217;s here, we move.<br />
Aram: [ On phone ] Okay, I just got word from the Bomb Squad. Preliminary sweep says they found no explosive devices on site.<br />
Samar: No device? How is that possible?<br />
Aram: And another thing, and I know this is so not the time, but, uh I was grabbing some, uh, UN reports for Agent Ressler from your office. And while I was there, uh, I noticed a few discarded incident reports in the trash.<br />
Samar: You&#8217;re right. This isn&#8217;t the time.<br />
Aram: After what you did in the field, I thought I&#8217;d overreacted, but these mistakes, they are, um what you were having trouble with is ‚Äì is basic. I had no idea how much damage has been done.<br />
Ziegler: [ COUGHING ]<br />
Samar: I have to call you back.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ressler: They didn&#8217;t find the device?<br />
Samar: Not yet, but they will.<br />
Ressler: That&#8217;s weird, right?<br />
Samar: The important thing is that everyone&#8217;s okay.<br />
Ziegler: [ COUGHS ]<br />
Hartmans: Let me get you a glass of water.<br />
Ziegler: [ COUGHING CONTINUES ]<br />
Senator Wade: [ To Ziegler ] Does this have anything to do with the threat you started to tell me about? This dossier?<br />
Ressler: Why wouldn&#8217;t they find a device? I mean, Moreau paid off Kruger to get advance team access to get inside the secure cordon, but why?<br />
Samar: Maybe it wasn&#8217;t a device?<br />
Ressler: Maybe there was another way. I mean, maybe it wasn&#8217;t a bomb or an explosion, but another way to carry out the hit.<br />
Ziegler: [ COUGHING ] [ She coughs out one of General Shiro‚Äôs weaponized beetles ]<br />
‚Äî Help! We need some help here!<br />
‚Äî We need a medic!<br />
Ziegler: [ COUGHS ]<br />
[ Ziegler collapses. The beetles pour out of her mouth and nose ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper and Panabaker are being driven back from the White House ]<br />
Cooper: [ On phone ] Right. [ CELLPHONE BEEPS ] That was Ressler. Ziegler is dead.<br />
Panabaker: What? How? I thought she was safe.<br />
Cooper: Reddington knew. He&#8217;s known all along. He sent us after the Bug Man. Turn around.<br />
[ TIRES SCREECH ]<br />
Panabaker: W-Wait. What are you talking about?<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;re going back to the White House. Reddington gave us a Blacklister weeks ago a scientist upset with how we&#8217;re killing off insects, so he created one to kill us off. Some kind of a super beetle ‚Äì the kind that killed Ziegler.<br />
Panabaker: And you want to go tell the President, &#8220;I told you so&#8221;?<br />
Cooper: I want to tell the President how to find the assassin.<br />
Panabaker: Do you know how to find him?<br />
Cooper: No, but Reddington does.<br />
Panabaker:  Diaz has made up his mind.<br />
Cooper: Well, by my watch, it&#8217;s 11:51.That gives him 10 minutes to change it. Or I&#8217;m gonna tell The New York Times that he could&#8217;ve saved the life of Germany&#8217;s top intelligence officer but chose not to.<br />
Panabaker: That would be career suicide.<br />
Cooper: Yes. For the President.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is escorted through the corridors to the execution chamber ]<br />
[ DOOR SLIDING SHUT ECHOING ] [ CLANK ECHOES ]<br />
[ UNKLE&#8217;s ‚ô™ &#8220;Farewell&#8221; plays ]<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:12 Bastien Moreau, Pt 2 (‚Ññ 20)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red has 10 minutes left to live. He is strapped to an execution table at the Federal Penitentiary in Terre Haute, Indiana, waiting for a lethal injection. Cooper has just learned that Ava Ziegler, the head of German National Intelligence, has been assassinated on US soil, as Red had predicted. Cooper has ordered the vehicle he is in with the CIA‚Äôs Cynthia Panabaker, to return to the White House for one final plea to President Robert Diaz to spare Red‚Äôs life so Red can help unveil a broader conspiracy against the United States. The plot is revealed in a dossier provided to German Intelligence by MI6, the British Intelligence Service. It appears, however, that Diaz is unlikely to be moved since Diaz himself ‚Äì unbeknownst to either Red or Cooper ‚Äì is behind the plot.</p>
<p>President Diaz tasked DOJ official Anna McMahon to squelch the dossier. For this, she turned to Bastien Moreau, who works to enable anti-globalist, ultra-nationalist causes. He had his appearance changed by plastic surgeon Dr Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33 in Episode 6:1), who he subsequently killed. He needed a new identity to get by security to attempt to bomb the United Nations (Episode 6:2), also at the behest of McMahon and Diaz. The plot failed when Red engaged the help of Maxwell Ruddiger, who had created the bomb. Moreau escaped then, and is now under pressure from Diaz and McMahon not only to squelch the dossier and accomplish what the U.N. bomb plan failed to achieve.</p>
<p>After killing Ava Ziegler using the weaponized beetles developed by General Shiro (Blacklister #116), Moreau now has ex-MI6 agent Christopher Miles at gunpoint in Miles‚Äôs hotel room, demanding the dossier, which Miles claims not to have. </p>
<p>Liz and Dembe are waiting to witness Red‚Äôs execution. Liz spent Red‚Äôs last meal with him. He spoke of his childhood, especially his mother (‚ÄúMy mother understood the problems of the human heart in conflict with itself. So she understood Everything‚Äù), and is calm facing death. Liz had intended to press Red on the question of his true identity, but in a sudden change of heart, said to him, simply ‚Äì for the first time ‚Äì ‚ÄúI love you.‚Äù His reaction was stunned astonishment. </p>
<p>Now at ten minutes and counting to 12:01 a.m., it appears that Red‚Äôs fate is sealed.
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:13 Robert Vesco (‚Ññ 9)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): By revealing the man behind the murder of Ava Ziegler, the head of German Intelligence, Red has escaped execution and his immunity agreement has been restored. The murderer, Bastien Moreau, ‚ÄúThe Corsican‚Äù (Blacklister #20), was part of a plot approved by President Robert Diaz and orchestrated by Deputy AG Anna McMahon, the very people who were compelled to grant Red clemency or have their own aims exposed. Red believes McMahon is behind the plot, but cannot prove it and McMahon has put herself in charge of the Task Force. </p>
<p>The aims of the conspiracy against the United States are unknown but are described in a dossier compiled by former MI6 agent Christopher Miles. All those (besides the conspirators) who knew its details are now dead. Both Miles and Ziegler were killed by Moreau who was also able to read it when Red provided him with the password which Miles had whispered to Samar just before he died after being shot by Moreau. Moreau, an extreme nationalist, was horrified that he had been tricked by his handler McMahon. He thought he was working with the ‚ÄúBlack Fist,‚Äù an extreme nationalist group. Instead, the dossier laid out a plot against America. So, instead of killing Red at McMahon‚Äôs request, Moreau did an about-face and turned his sights on her.</p>
<p>Red alerted the task force that Moreau‚Äôs next target would be McMahon, and Liz and Ressler were able to apprehend him. However, he was quickly taken out by a sniper who turned out to be McMahon‚Äôs henchman ‚ÄúMr Sandquist.‚Äù Before his arrest, Moreau ditched the drive containing the dossier along the sidewalk. So the nature of the plot remains unknown to the Task Force but they are determined to unveil it, working at cross-purposes with the very DOJ under whose purview they exist.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A hotel kitchen ]<br />
[ Les Brown‚Äôs ‚ô™ ‚ÄúBruised Bones‚Äù (Jazz) plays softly ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Fabricio?<br />
Fabricio: ¬≠Yes, sir?<br />
<b>Red:</b> They need help in the back room. More servers. At least one. Maybe two.<br />

<b>Red:</b> And, also, let&#8217;s open another couple of cases of the Reserva. And, please, tell Amelia to keep the drinks flowing. Champagne, the wines, cocktails. I don&#8217;t care if they&#8217;re drinking milk ‚Äì I don&#8217;t want an empty glass out there.<br />

<b>Red:</b> Oh, it&#8217;s good to be had.</p>

<b>Red:</b> Good to see you guys.<br />
[ Glen Carter walks up with a full plate of jumbo shrimp ]<br />
Glen: Hey! There you are. We&#8217;ve got a situation at the buffet.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, dear. What&#8217;s wrong?<br />
Glen: You&#8217;re out of those jumbo shrimps. I let the kitchen know. [ CHUCKLES ] Hey, uh, while I got ya, I&#8217;ve been meaning to apologize about that whole jury mix-up. I feel real bad.<br />

<b>Red:</b> Thank you for coming, Glen.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Samar has an MRI of her brain ] [ MRI MACHINE CLICKING ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Samar is home with Aram ]<br />
Samar: I went to the neurologist for another MRI. The headaches, the ¬≠forgetfulness, the confusion ‚Äì it&#8217;s all symptomatic of something called vascular dementia. Apparently I have been having a series of mini-strokes. I don&#8217;t feel them. I don&#8217;t know that they&#8217;re happening. But they are, and each one causes damage.<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m glad you resigned. That gives us the time to get you the treatment that you need.<br />
Samar: It&#8217;s not just work. It&#8217;s family, too. Aram, I can&#8217;t have kids.<br />
Aram: Let&#8217;s just stick to one major life decision at a time.<br />
Samar: We have to talk about this.<br />
Aram: And we will. After you get better.<br />
Samar: I&#8217;m up for anything but false hope. No anger, no denial. No bargaining, no depression.<br />
Can you do that for me?<br />
Aram: No.<br />
Samar: Okay, then please promise me this ‚Äì don&#8217;t tell anyone about my condition. I don&#8217;t want them to know.<br />
Aram: Of course. That I can do.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ After Red‚Äôs party, a handful of guests remain, and Liz. Red is sipping a Bloody Mary. His speech is slightly slurred ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Walt Whitman lived in a boarding house at this address during the Civil War. Did you know he was an ardent prohibitionist? Imagine that ‚Äì a sober poet. [ SLURPS ] Mmm! Have I ever told you about my mentor?<br />
Liz: You mean, somebody actually taught you how to drink this early?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Is it early? I thought it was late. Robert Vesco. Robert took me under his wing. He taught me how to be a fugitive. I trusted him with my life and my life&#8217;s savings. Which he convinced me to invest in a cattle ranch in Paraguay. Or so I thought, until I went down there and found out it was a whorehouse just outside of Asunci√≥n.<br />
Liz: He conned you.<br />
Robert: Out of everything. I got my first taste for vengeance ‚Äì which I was never able to satisfy.<br />
Liz: Why not?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because Vesco up and died on me. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office. Liz briefs the Task Force ]<br />
Liz: Robert Vesco was a central player in American financial and political scandals in the 1970s. In 1971, the SEC accused Vesco of looting $200 million out of a mutual fund he controlled. And a year later, Vesco made an illegal campaign contribution to Richard Nixon, hoping that Nixon&#8217;s attorney general would let him off the hook. And when he didn&#8217;t, Vesco fled the country, living the rest of his life in glamorous exile in Costa Rica, Nicaragua, The Bahamas, and Cuba, where he reportedly died in 2007.<br />
Aram: Reportedly?<br />
Liz: When Reddington was in prison, he heard a rumor ‚Äì that Vesco faked his death to avoid capture.<br />
Cooper: Does he have any proof?<br />
Liz: He sent Dembe to Havana to dig up his grave. He asked me to have the M.E. run the DNA on the remains he unearthed.<br />
Cooper: There was a time when the Bureau was actively hunting for Vesco, but we&#8217;re not anymore. If he did fake his death, I doubt it was to avoid capture.<br />
Liz: Reddington agrees. He thinks Vesco found the De La Cruz ‚Äì a Spanish ship filled with gold that sank off the coast of Florida in the 1700s. Vesco always told him that if he found that treasure, that he would disappear forever.<br />
Aram: Does Mr. Reddington know him?<br />
Liz: ¬≠Know him? Vesco was Reddington&#8217;s mentor until he swindled him out of every penny he had and left him high and dry in a whorehouse in Paraguay.<br />
Ressler: I like this guy already.<br />
Cooper: In the last 50 years, there have been two truly mythic fugitives ‚Äì Robert Vesco and Raymond Reddington. If one can help us get the other, I&#8217;m all for it. Ressler, Keen, find out where the M.E. is at with the remains.<br />
Samar: Before you do that, I want you to know that I&#8217;m resigning.<br />
Ressler: You&#8217;re leaving? For what? The Mossad?<br />
Samar: No, I&#8217;m leaving them, too.<br />
Cooper: Which reminds me they&#8217;ve called to schedule an exit interview. I know I speak for everyone when I say we&#8217;ll miss you and we&#8217;re happy for you.<br />
Samar: Thank you.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Medical Examiner: Pop quiz ‚Äì guess who&#8217;s buried in Vesco&#8217;s grave.<br />
Ressler: So it&#8217;s not Vesco?<br />
M.E.: No. His name was Anderson Mount.<br />
Liz: Who&#8217;s that?<br />
M.E.: Run-of-the-mill goon. His greatest hits. [ Gives Ressler a photo ] Did enough damage to get into CODIS. And when we put the DNA from the body into the system, we got a match.<br />
Ressler: Thanks, Doc.<br />
[ M.E. leaves ]<br />
Ressler: So, if Mount&#8217;s in Vesco&#8217;s grave maybe Vesco&#8217;s in Mount&#8217;s life.<br />
Liz: It says in his file, Mount was in Truro, Nova Scotia. If you want to get off the grid, you can&#8217;t get much further than that.<br />
Ressler: Looks like we&#8217;re going to Nova Scotia. In the middle of winter.<br />
Liz: Come on. We&#8217;re gonna need warmer clothes.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Samar shows up for her exit interview with the Mossad. She is met by Levi Shur, an agent with whom she previously had a romantic relationship ]<br />
Levi Shur: Hello, Samar.<br />

Levi: I hear congratulations are in order.<br />

Levi: Or Reddington. Hey. I&#8217;m just the messenger.<br />
Samar: Yeah, and the message I&#8217;m getting is that you think I have something to hide.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ In Truro, Nova Scotia, Liz and Ressler are parked in front of a rundown brownstone ]<br />

Ressler: I think we need to get the local police involved.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red and Vesco are in Red‚Äôs plane ]<br />

Vesco: Are you still upset about Asunci√≥n?<br />

Vesco: If it&#8217;s real, I believe I know where it is. I never went after it. Oh, I wanted to, but enemies were circling. I had to flee. So I staged my own death and I fled the country. And by the time the dust had settled, I-I realized that I had changed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;Changed.&#8221;<br />
Vesco: ¬≠I&#8217;d lost the itch. Walked away. Being forced to lie low and live the simple life was the best thing that could&#8217;ve happened to me. I-It forced me to turn the world off and to tune into myself.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, my God.<br />
Vesco: ¬≠I have my cat. I have plenty of glorious books.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Robert, you conned me once. I won&#8217;t be conned again.<br />
Vesco: Untether yourself from social expectations and this destructive life of crime and and look inward.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m happy to. ¬≠Right after I get the gold.<br />
Vesco: You can have it, Ray, but [ SIGHS ] It won&#8217;t give you inner peace.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I already have inner peace. What I could use is a new yacht. The last one was seized in Mallorca.<br />
Vesco: All right, I believe the gold is buried under the Old French Opera House in New Orleans. I can prove it to you, but we&#8217;ll have to reroute the jet.<br />
<b>Red:</b> To where?<br />
Vesco: ¬≠Washington. There isn&#8217;t a treasure map, but there is a clue trail in the Library of Congress.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Robert, if you&#8217;re lying, I will shatter your serenity by burning your home, drowning your cat, ¬≠and cutting off your big toes.<br />
Vesco: You wouldn&#8217;t dare drown my cat.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] Maybe not. But I will take the toes.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Samar‚Äôs office ] [ KNOCK ON DOOR ]<br />

Samar: They sent Levi. A friendly face to put me at ease while they administered a polygraph.<br />
Aram: They gave you a polygraph? Why?<br />
Samar: To make I wasn&#8217;t leaving because I&#8217;d been turned.<br />

Aram: [ Angrily ] Why? Why is that so urgent that it cannot wait until you get help or convince Levi that you didn&#8217;t dump him to join Hamas? He does know that I&#8217;m, like, a quarter Jewish, right? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Ressler: Reddington screwed us. Took Vesco for himself. He knew Vesco would have the local cops in his pocket, so he tipped them off that we were there.<br />
Samar: So he gets his revenge. Yesterday the world thought Vesco was dead. By tomorrow, he will be.<br />
Liz: Reddington wants more than revenge. He wants treasure.<br />
Cooper: The De La Cruz? Reddington said Vesco already found it.<br />
Ressler: Well, judging by his modest apartment, I&#8217;d say that if he knew where it was, he never found it.<br />
Liz: Reddington called us from his jet to give a gloating apology and to say the hunt was on.<br />
Cooper: Then let&#8217;s join in. If we solve the mystery, maybe we can get to the treasure first and arrest Vesco.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Library of Congress ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Robert, I appreciate that your love of literature is almost as keen as mine, but why on Earth are we in the Library of Congress?<br />
Vesco: Uh, you want to know how I decoded the myth and located my white whale? The answer is in the poem. &#8220;The Ballad of the De La Cruz.&#8221;<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Post Office ] <a id="returnvesco"></a><br />
Liz: It was written under a pseudonym. The author is a mystery, but when Reddington gave us this case, he said this poem somehow holds the key to where the gold was hidden. <a href="#triviakeyvesco">üîò [See Note]</a><br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Vesco: The poem is an opera singer&#8217;s lament about a Spanish ship bringing silver and gold to the American colonies during the Revolution. But the ship sank in a storm somewhere along the East Coast, killing over 120 men aboard and sending over half a ton of gold and treasure into the deep.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ressler: We had the NSA run the text through decryption and steganography programs. They came up empty. If there&#8217;s a secret hidden in that text ‚Äì they couldn&#8217;t find it.<br />
Samar: Maybe it&#8217;s in the subtext. Storms. Marauders. Dates and times.<br />
Ressler: Who&#8217;d know about that? The Naval College?<br />
Aram: The Library of Congress. They have more primary source material than any library in the world.<br />
Cooper: Keen, Ressler. Get there. Decode the poem. Samar, Aram, you&#8217;re on Reddington. I want him found.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Vesco: According to the poem, the De La Cruz sank the spring of 1778. But there&#8217;s no record of any storm big enough to take down a galleon of that size. So I started thinking ‚Äì what if it never sank? What if the &#8220;storm&#8221; that presumably destroyed the De La Cruz was actually a metaphor<br />
<b>Red:</b> For something else catastrophic.<br />
Vesco: Or someone.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It didn&#8217;t sink. It was taken.<br />
Vesco: The De La Cruz was headed to Philadelphia. The route from southern waters would take it right past what used to be known as Hell&#8217;s Gate, an area known to be frequented by pirates. Uh-hah. Enter Ernesto Hidalgo. Criminal. Cheat. Pirate. Drunk. He and his men dominated that area at the time.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How can you be sure he was the one who took the galleon?<br />
Vesco: Because Hidalgo and his men were in all the papers in the months before May 1778. But afterwards? Nothing. He took the treasure and he fled inland. Naval records indicated the Navy hunted them down, killing Hidalgo and his entire crew near New Orleans. But there&#8217;s no mention of any recovered treasure. Hidalgo hid it somewhere before he died. The question is where.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;Enter Judith Snell, one of the most famous opera singers of her time. Heh. Just like the poem. Apparently, Judith liked to hang around with the bad boys. And the papers of the day were full of her exploits with any number of rogues and scoundrels, Hidalgo being one. And I believe that he gave her the task of hiding the bounty in a place where nobody would dare look ‚Äì her dressing room in the opera house in New Orleans which later burned to the ground, killing her and 28 others.<br />
&emsp;&emsp;My theory? Whatever remains of Judith Snell&#8217;s dressing room is located here, directly under the stage of the new opera house, which was built on the remains of the old one. If the treasure&#8217;s real, it&#8217;s there.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What a tale. An opera. A romance with pirates. A fire. Shipwrecks and gold. Just the sort of thing that gets me out of bed in the morning.<br />
Vesco: It won&#8217;t make you happy, Ray. It won&#8217;t make you whole.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, but you&#8217;re wrong. It will make me happy. Very. Dembe, phone Ruddiger. Tell him to sober up. We&#8217;re gonna rob the opera.</p>

Ressler: [ LAUGHS ] A reformed fugitive.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Sworn off greed and avarice.<br />
Liz: So you commuted his sentence? Like the President commuted yours?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, and in honor of his ascetic existence, I&#8217;ve decided to hand over $100-something million worth of 18th-century gold.<br />
Ressler: You&#8217;re just gonna give it to us?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Every last doubloon. It&#8217;s inside.<br />
[ Red opens the cargo door ]<br />
Ressler: Or it isn&#8217;t.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Flashback:</b><br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m in your debt, my friend.<br />
Vesco: Ohh. Believe me, Ray. You&#8217;ve more than repaid your debt.<br />
[ ‚ãô Vesco lifts the truck keys from Red‚Äôs pocket ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Liz: [ LAUGHS ] He&#8217;s reformed, is he? &#8220;Given up greed and avarice&#8221;?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Do you have a phone?<br />

<b>Red:</b> Come on. Take my picture. It&#8217;s not often I get egg on my face. But to be egged by the same person twice? That needs memorializing.<br />
Ressler: You think this is funny? This was a complete waste of time.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Waste of time? We&#8217;ve been decrypting legends. Chasing pirates. Hunting hidden treasure.<br />
Ressler: And come up empty. We lost Vesco.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How can you lose something you never had? I gave you a Blacklister you thought was dead. Now that you know he&#8217;s alive, you can hunt him down. Plus, you witnessed my humiliation. I think that would salve any wound.<br />
Liz: It doesn&#8217;t. But it&#8217;s a start.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Get in here, Dembe. I see a little yolk on your cheek. [ SIGHS ]<br />
Liz: Smile, suckers. [ Laughs ]<br />
[ CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Vesco drives the truck with the gold ]<br />
Vesco: [ LAUGHING ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:14 Osterman Umbrella Co (‚Ññ 6)</h2>

Program air date: 3/29/2019 in the US<br />

Entertainment Weekly Recap: <a href="http://bit.ly/2uzJ4WH" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/2uzJ4WH</a> (recap for both 6:13 and 6:14)<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:14 Osterman Umbrella Co (‚Ññ 6)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): For the second time, Red has been snookered out of a fortune by his former mentor, Robert Vesco (Blacklister #9), the man who had supposedly taught him not to trust anyone. Well, it‚Äôs never too late to learn. Besides, there were pirates and treasure and thieves and scoundrels and opera! </p>
<p>Behind this caper, however, a darker story loomed as Samar attempted to hide the fact that she has vascular dementia, a degenerative brain condition resulting from her nearly drowning. She is experiencing a series of mini-strokes, each resulting in brain damage affecting her language skills, perception and judgment. The condition led to her failure in the field to save the life of MI6 agent Christopher Miles after which she told Cooper she would be resigning from the task force though she would not tell him why. Worse, in her exit interview with Mossad, she lied on a polygraph, saying she was pregnant instead. Her former Mossad boyfriend, Levi Shur, approached Aram and told him she had failed the polygraph. Thinking it would help her, Aram told Levi about Samar‚Äôs condition, after which Levi mentioned Samar‚Äôs ‚Äúpregnancy‚Äù and congratulated him.</p>
<p>Aram was thrilled by the news until Samar told him it was only a lie she had been forced to tell. She said she would not be able to raise a child because of her condition. Aram, though disappointed, reavowed his love for Samar, come what may.</p>
<p>The now-dead MI6 agent Christopher Miles had held the secret of a plot against the interests of the United States perpetrated by none other than President Robert Diaz, DOJ official Anna McMahon, and a shady security guard and hit man ‚ÄúMr Sandquist.‚Äù Anna McMahon has her sights set on eliminating Red who she thinks knows more about the plot than he does. All those who actually knew of the plot besides the perpetrators are now the dead. But the dossier compiled by Miles describing the plot still exists. Bastien Moreau (Blacklister #20) ditched the flash drive containing the dossier along a sidewalk before being gunned down by Mr Sandquist. The flash drive was picked up by a young boy who brought it home in his backpack.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Singapore ]<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ] [ A man opens a hotel door and takes delivery of a bulky manila envelope. He takes out a pawn (chess piece). On the bottom is stamped ‚Äú242.‚Äù A woman descends the staircase in the suite ]<br />
[ They speak Mandarin ]<br />
Woman: Strange. What does it mean?<br />
Man: That I need to leave.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ The man descends a stairs in a vertical mall. It is crowded. He sees a couple talking next to a railing overlooking an atrium. Turning the ring on his pinkie finger to face inward, he removes the stone from the ring, exposing a needle. He walks close to the couple talking, brushes the woman‚Äôs hand and walks away. The woman looks at her hand. It is bleeding ]<br />
Man: [ Mandarin ] What‚Äôs wrong, angel?<br />
Woman: [ Mandarin ] Something stung me.<br />
[ The woman‚Äôs mouth gapes open, her pupils dilate and turn whitish blue and she tumbles over the railing to the floor of the atrium ] [ ‚ÄºÔ∏è‚ö°Ô∏èCrash‚ö°Ô∏è‚ÄºÔ∏è] [ Onlookers gasp ] [ PEOPLE SHOUTING ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram and Samar‚Äôs apartment in DC. Samar is still in bed ]<br />
[ DOOR OPENS ] [ Aram enters carrying a breakfast tray ]<br />
Aram: [ SINGSONG VOICE ] Rise and shine.<br />
Samar: You&#8217;re up early.<br />
Aram: It has been a morning. Two small grease fires in the kitchen, one almost-disastrous juicing mishap. But, voil√°. Breakfast in bed.<br />
Samar: What&#8217;s on the menu?<br />
Aram: French toast, hash browns ‚Äì all your favorites.<br />
Samar: Those are none of my favorites, but I love you anyway.<br />
Aram: Well, I got the orange juice right, uh, fresh-squeezed. But, um, careful ‚Äì might be a part of my finger in there.<br />
Samar: What&#8217;s the occasion?<br />
Aram: I thought you&#8217;d want a full stomach before our trip.<br />
Samar: Our trip? Where we going?<br />
Aram: The Lodge at Glenforest. Rural Pennsylvania. Three days, two nights. Our own cabin in the woods. Dinners in the main lodge, crackling fires. I look really, really good in flannel. What do you think?<br />
Samar: It sounds amazing, but don&#8217;t they need you at work? I&#8217;m the only one retiring.<br />
Aram: I cleared it with Mr. Cooper. The team can manage. It&#8217;s not like the world&#8217;s gonna end.<br />
Samar: Aram, we worked together, remember? We both know the world could literally end if you&#8217;re not there.<br />
Aram: It&#8217;s a few days. Eat up. I&#8217;ll pack.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs flat with the old photos ] [ Red is drinking a green health concoction ]<br />
Dembe: He will be pleased to hear it. Yes. As soon as possible.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ahh.<br />
[ CELLPHONE BEEPS ]<br />
Dembe: That was Spalding Stark.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where is he on the clinical trials?<br />
Dembe: Blind testing.<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ]<br />
Dembe: He&#8217;s almost ready to deliver. [ Opens door ] Elizabeth.<br />
Liz: Dembe.<br />
[ DOOR CLOSES ]<br />
Liz: Health kick?<br />
<b>Red:</b> They say what doesn&#8217;t kill you makes you stronger. [ GROANS ] They&#8217;re wrong.<br />
[ Liz looks at the photograph of herself as a child on a swing with her mother, Katarina Rostova ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your mother loved that photograph. Represented everything she wanted but couldn&#8217;t have. Not after she betrayed the KGB. After that, she was a hunted woman.<br />
Liz: Burned agents always are.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hunted by the Osterman Umbrella Company.<br />
Liz: Something tells me they don&#8217;t sell umbrellas.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A burn notice can mean kill or capture. When it&#8217;s kill, they&#8217;re the hit squad of choice.<br />
Liz: The KGB farms out hits?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The KGB. The CIA. MI6. SID. Over the years, most agencies have come to the conclusion that terminating their own was bad for business. It strained loyalties, created tension within the ranks. Where most agencies agree on nothing else, this they agree on ‚Äì that a neutral third party is critical in the elimination of their own operatives.<br />
Liz: The world&#8217;s intelligence agencies have a go-to company for contract kills?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of their own agents, yes.<br />
Liz: They sent killers after my mother?<br />
<b>Red:</b> They did. Which is all the incentive I need to put them on the Blacklist, but as the FBI may need a bit more bait on the hook, there is this ‚Äì typically, the Umbrella Company operates on foreign soil, but I&#8217;ve been led to believe their next target is here in the United States.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office. Liz briefs the Task Force ]<br />
Liz: Kevin Major, Nicolai Druganin, Shirley Wei. All agents for MI6, FSB, and the Singapore Security and Intelligence Division, who Reddington claims were murdered by the Osterman Umbrella Company.<br />
Cooper: Their agencies claim they were patriots killed in action.<br />
Liz: Reddington says they were traitors that their agencies had terminated.<br />
Cooper: He says the CIA&#8217;s involved?<br />
Ressler: Which part? Targeting your own agents for murder or farming out the hits?<br />
Liz: Not only is the CIA involved, but that the next hit&#8217;s going to take place in America.<br />
Cooper: Not if we can help it, it&#8217;s not.<br />
Liz: He made it sound like this was accepted practice.<br />
Cooper: Maybe it is, but that doesn&#8217;t make it right. There&#8217;s someone I can reach out to at Langley. I&#8217;ll get to the bottom of this.<br />
Liz: How well do you know them?<br />
Cooper: I introduced him to his first wife. Let&#8217;s hope he&#8217;s forgiven me.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At a counter drinking coffee ]<br />
Cooper: What can you tell me about a group commissioned to scrub rogue agents? The Osterman Umbrella Company.<br />
Lansky: I can tell you that you shouldn&#8217;t be asking about them.<br />
Cooper: I wouldn&#8217;t be if they only operated abroad. That&#8217;s your turf. But, uh, from what I hear, their next target&#8217;s stateside, and that turf&#8217;s mine.<br />
Lansky: I can&#8217;t confirm or deny.<br />
Cooper: An American is gonna be killed. No trial, no due process. Killed.<br />
Lansky: I can&#8217;t confirm or deny because I don&#8217;t know.<br />
Cooper: You expect me to believe that? You&#8217;re the C.O.O.<br />
Lansky: Maybe you got bad intel.<br />
Cooper: My intel&#8217;s never bad.<br />
Lansky: If an American&#8217;s being targeted, it wasn&#8217;t sanctioned by anyone I know.<br />
Cooper: So, what? This Umbrella Company is operating on its own now?<br />
Lansky: I told you I don&#8217;t know. But I intend on finding out.<br />
Cooper: You better find out fast. A person&#8217;s life is at risk.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ ELEVATOR BELL DINGS ] [ A young blonde woman, Rachael, exits the elevator, leaving her motorcycle behind. There is a bank of padlocked doors. She looks at black token ‚Äú006‚Äù and makes her way to a door marked ‚ÄúFloor 5 Aisle 1 Room 006.‚Äù She unlocks the padlock and enters, walking to an enclosure with a briefcase on a table. She puts the chess piece, a pawn, down on the table. She opens the briefcase and looks a paperclipped document of 25 pages or so. Also in the briefcase is a jewelry box containing a ring with a large red stone. She puts the ring on her right ring finger ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ BELL JINGLES, DOOR CLOSES ] [ Lansky enters a shop with neon signs saying ‚ÄúShoe Repair‚Äù and displaying umbrellas ]<br />
Lansky: It&#8217;s supposed to rain today.<br />
Attendant: You got the wrong forecast.<br />
Lansky: Best to be prepared.<br />
[ The attendant hands Lansky an umbrella ]<br />
[ Lansky exits the shop. where Cooper is standing. He pulls the neck of the umbrella out of the sheath, revealing a phone number (617) 555-0184 ]<br />
[ HORNS HONKING ]<br />
Lansky: This is a bad idea.<br />
Cooper: Worse than murdering an American citizen?<br />
Lansky: [ On phone ] I&#8217;d like to arrange a meeting.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS ] [ Cooper walks up to a black man, Hobbs, who sits on a bench along the sidewalk. Cooper sits next to him ]<br />
Cooper: My name&#8217;s Harold Cooper. I&#8217;m the Deputy Director of the FBI.<br />
Hobbs: There must be some misunderstanding.<br />
Cooper: Yes, I believe there is. You thinking you can get away with murder. I&#8217;ve spoken with Lansky.<br />
Hobbs: Lansky is misinformed.<br />
Cooper: Lansky wasn&#8217;t informed. I informed Lansky, and now I&#8217;m informing you. I know about the Umbrella Company. I know what you do. You do it here, I&#8217;ll make sure you&#8217;re prosecuted.<br />
Hobbs: He was misinformed.<br />
Cooper: Has a contract been ordered on an American agent?<br />
Hobbs: I have very powerful friends.<br />
Cooper: I have handcuffs and backup. They&#8217;ll come here in cars with sirens and lights. Makes quite a scene.<br />
Hobbs: An American agent. Is that what you asked me before?<br />
Cooper: Is one being targeted?<br />
Hobbs: At this time, the Company has no outstanding tokens on American operatives.<br />
Cooper: Tokens. You people are so antiseptic.<br />
Hobbs: Are we through here?<br />
Cooper: For now.<br />
[ Hobbs gets up and walks away. He has an umbrella ]<br />
[ Liz is with Ressler in a car parked nearby ] [ ENGINE STARTS, SHIFTER CLICKS ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Ressler: We tailed him to his office.<br />
Cooper: Global Systems Imports.<br />
Ressler: DCRA records show that it incorporated in &#8217;87. Taxes, license fees are paid up. Top executives are pillars of the community, not a parking ticket among them.<br />
Liz: Which is why we couldn&#8217;t pull a search warrant.<br />
Ressler: We could sweat the executives. They&#8217;re covering for the Umbrella Company or at least work for it.<br />
Cooper: If they&#8217;re anything like Hobbs, they won&#8217;t sweat easily.<br />
Liz: They would if we turned up the heat.<br />
Cooper: And how do you propose we do that? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A busy street. It‚Äôs raining. Dembe comes up behind Hobbs ]<br />

[üö®SIRENS WAILINGüö®]<br />
Aram: Where you at?<br />

Aram: Samar! </p>
