<blockquote><p>
MAN ON RADIO: Adam-12. This is a 10-33.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Samar and Aram walk quickly through the woods ]<br />
Aram: Those guys really won&#8217;t stop, will they?<br />
Samar: Never. That&#8217;s why I have to go. Someone else will get killed.<br />
Aram: Samar.<br />
Samar: I don&#8217;t want it to be you, and I don&#8217;t want someone caught in the crossfire.<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m fine with that, but what you said back at the car doesn&#8217;t work for me. I&#8217;m coming with you.<br />
Samar: No. Aram.<br />
Aram: Listen. Listen to me. Listen. You say you don&#8217;t want me to go through that ‚Äì the new life, the never looking back ‚Äì but you do not have the right to make that decision for me. You cannot force me to live without you. That is not living. This is my decision, and I&#8217;m coming with you.<br />
Samar: Okay, but if we do that, we have to move quickly and leave zero footprint.<br />
Aram: I have small feet.<br />
Samar: The first thing is getting out of the country. The Umbrella group will be monitoring airports, subways, train stations.<br />
Aram: Okay, we need to tell Mr. Cooper. I know he&#8217;d help in any way he can.<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s not a bad idea, but to do that, we&#8217;ll have to split up.<br />
Aram: Whoa. I thought you said we&#8217;re in this together.<br />
Samar: We are. I&#8217;m not ditching you. But- But I can&#8217;t go back to the office. The whole place will be under surveillance. To do this, you&#8217;ll have to go in alone, tell Cooper what&#8217;s going on, and get him to arrange safe passage for us.<br />
Aram: All right. Passage to where?<br />
Samar: I don&#8217;t know. I&#8217;ve got friends abroad. Europe, maybe. Asia.<br />
Aram: Okay. Okay. But what are you gonna do?<br />
Samar: I&#8217;m gonna try and stay alive. Do you remember the loft building on Meredith?<br />
Aram: Yeah. That safe house.<br />
Samar: Meet me there with Cooper in three hours. And we&#8217;re gone.<br />
Aram: Please. You be safe.<br />
Samar: Like the rest of our lives depended on it.<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

The better the company man, the less it matters what the rules are, how ethical they are, how just, how humane. In your company, the rules called for you to kill a good and decent person, a colleague and partner. And you followed those rules blindly and without question.<br />
Levi: Samar would have done the same to me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Which only proves my point ‚Äì that the company can corrupt even the best among us.<br />
Levi: You&#8217;re acting like I wanted this to happen. I didn&#8217;t. This is the last thing I wanted.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And yet you did it anyway.<br />
Levi: Look, you&#8217;re upset. I get it. I am too. We feel the same way about this.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, I don&#8217;t believe we do. What I really can&#8217;t get is how you used Agent Mojtabai, how you manipulated him into telling you about Samar&#8217;s condition. He told you so as to protect her, but because of you, he has to live with the fact that he betrayed her, that his words put a target on her back, that he is the reason that they will never be together again. Aram trusted you, and because of that trust, his life has been devastated.<br />
Levi: I was just doing my job.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. And I suppose I&#8217;m just doing mine.<br />
[ Red takes a plastic bag out of his coat pocket and puts it over Levi‚Äôs head, wrapping it tightly ]<br />
Levi: No. No. No. No! No! [ MUFFLED ] No! No! No! </p>

[ Aram waits in a garage ] [ ENGINE SHUTS OFF, DOORS OPENING ] [ Cooper, Ressler and Liz get out ]<br />

Aram: Thank you, sir.<br />
Ressler: This is the number of a friend of mine, ex-Special Forces. He does some work in Southeast Asia, so, after Taipei, give him a call. Use my name. He can get you set up anywhere.<br />
[ Liz draws Aram aside ] [ Hug ]<br />
Liz: Are you sure this is what you want?<br />
Aram: You know, she&#8217;s always asking me that, and I honestly don&#8217;t know why. To me, it is it&#8217;s so simple. I just I want to be with the person I love, and I love her. So yeah, it&#8217;s what I want.<br />
Liz: The reason she&#8217;s asking you that is because, for most people, it isn&#8217;t so simple.<br />
Aram: [ To all ] I don&#8217;t think Samar or I would be safe, alive, or even together if it weren&#8217;t for everything you&#8217;ve done for us over the years. Thank you. Uh, those, um‚Äì those words seem so small compared to what you&#8217;ve done.<br />
Cooper: Those words are plenty. You&#8217;ve always looked out for us ‚Äì you and Agent Navabi. Now it&#8217;s our turn to look out for the two of you.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:15 Olivia Olson (‚Ññ 115)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Samar is gone, spirited away by Red at her request after a contract on her life was taken out by Mossad with the relentless and amoral Osterman Umbrella Company (Blacklister #6), the go-to organization for spy agencies world-wide seeking to eliminate their own agents when they came to be deemed security risks. In Samar‚Äôs case, this was because she failed a polygraph test when she lied to cover up the fact that she had a deteriorating mental condition, vascular dementia, a result of her nearly drowning. In time, her condition could mean she might no longer be able to keep a secret. </p>
<p>Aram insisted on making plans with Samar to accompany her into a new life set up for them by Cooper, but Samar knew this could never be, and reached out to Red instead. She knew she would have to leave Aram behind. Aram, however, cannot accept that Red was acting in good faith and cannot bear the loss of Samar. Inconsolable and furious, he slugged Red and declared he would never forgive him.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the matter remains that the Reddington Task Force is now under the purview of the DOJ‚Äôs Deputy Director Anna McMahon, who believes Red has become aware of a plot against the interests of the United States being perpetrated by herself and no less than President Robert Diaz, in complicity with a henchman, tracker and assassin, ‚ÄúMr Sandquist.‚Äù Red has no direct knowledge of the details of the plot, but McMahon suspects he does. The three people who did know ‚Äì the Director of German Intelligence Ava Ziegler, ex-MI6 Agent Christopher Miles, and contract killer Bastien Moreau (Blacklister #20) ‚Äì have all been assassinated. The only proof of the plot is a document, a dossier compiled by ex-MI6 Agent Miles. It is contained on a flash drive which was ditched by Moreau along a sidewalk and randomly picked up by a young boy who brought it home in his backpack.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ BELL DINGS ] [ Police Chief Devin Walker is having a meal in a restaurant. A man with a shaved head (Mr Coleman) sits down across the table from him ]<br />
Police Chief Walker: You need help?<br />
[ Coleman places an metal impact-resistant briefcase on the table ]<br />
Walker: What is this? Hey. I&#8217;m talking to you.<br />
[ Coleman hands Walker a manila file folder. Inside are photos of him meeting with drug dealers ]<br />
[ BELL DINGS ] [ Coleman has left the restaurant ] [ Walker opens the briefcase. Inside is a laptop with earphones. He puts the earphones in his ears and turns on the laptop ]<br />
Olivia Olson: [ On live video; British accent ] Hello, Chief Walker. Sorry to interrupt your meal‚Äì<br />
Walker: Who the hell are you?<br />
Olson: Who I am is immaterial. What matters is that I know you. I know, for example, you&#8217;re the top cop in a city consumed by an opioid epidemic. I know the Saleri Cartel have had remarkable success moving product on your streets, and I know why. You&#8217;re protecting them‚Äì<br />
Walker: Whatever you think you&#8217;re doing‚Äì<br />
Olson: ‚Äìyou and a cadre of corrupt underlings. I&#8217;ve provided a sample of the kind of proof that my team has gathered. Copies, actually. It&#8217;s all quite well documented ‚Äì the warnings of impending raids, the secure transport your men have provided, the cartel members you&#8217;ve neglected to arrest.<br />
Walker: What do you want? What is this?<br />
Olson: A notification. We&#8217;re not asking you to stop anything, we&#8217;ve simply decided to change your employer.<br />
Walker: My employer?<br />
Olson: I&#8217;ve been retained by the Tuerto Organization. You report to them now. The Saleris are done. You can arrest them or kill them, my client doesn&#8217;t care. Do as you&#8217;re told, and you&#8217;ll be hailed as a hero for ending the Saleri era. Ignore my instructions, and you&#8217;ll be destroyed. Publicly and permanently.  Okay, then. Goodnight, Chief.<br />
[ The keyboard hisses and‚ö°Ô∏èsparks‚ö°Ô∏è ] [ ELECTRICITY POPPING ] [ LATCHES CLICKING ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram writes on a notepad. He rips off the top sheet, folds it and puts it in an envelope. He makes a phone call ]<br />
Aram: Uh, yes. I&#8217;d like to close my account. The authorization codes? Of course yes, I&#8217;m ready. Access Delta 6-3-9. Echo-Uniform-Whiskey. That&#8217;s right. Liquidate everything. All $60 million.<br />
[ Aram picks up the three envelopes labeled ‚ÄúMr Cooper,‚Äù ‚ÄúRessler‚Äù and ‚ÄúLiz‚Äù and stuffs them in his backpack ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red flicks a syringe and gives himself a shot ] [ KNOCK ON DOOR ]<br />
Dembe: [ EXHALES SHARPLY ] Raymond. It&#8217;s Elizabeth.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Just hold on one sec.<br />
[ Red pulls up his pants ] [ ZIPPING ] [ He puts the syringe in a small black travel case and takes a pill with a glass of water ]<br />
[ Dembe lets Liz in ]<br />
Liz: [ SIGHS ] Why is it that men think the only way to handle a problem is to be stoic?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because Gary Cooper or Henry Fonda or Gregory Peck have taught us that&#8217;s how a man should deal with a problem.<br />
Liz: Aram is completely shut down.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have a competitor I want you to take out of the competition.<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s gonna implode.<br />
[ PAPER RUSTLES ] [ Red shows Liz a newspaper article: ‚ÄúHail to the Chief. Top Cop Ends Drug Cartel‚Äôs Long and Lethal Reign‚Äù ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Only time will mend Aram&#8217;s broken heart. Or revenge.<br />
Liz: You want us to take down an honest cop?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The chief is not my competition. Nor is he honest. He used to work for one cartel. Now he works for a more powerful one. My competition is the woman who convinced him to switch sides.<br />
Liz: She helps one criminal organization take over another?<br />
<b>Red:</b> She helps them expand. By identifying targets. Organizations vulnerable to hostile takeovers ‚Äì businesses or individuals whose debt can be leveraged, or, in this case, a cop who&#8217;s susceptible to persuasion.<br />
Liz: Are you siccing us on a criminal or a corporate raider?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ CHUCKLES ] Corporate CEOs are slavishly beholden to quarterly earnings, often sacrificing long-term strategy for short-term gain. Well, CEOs of criminal enterprises may not have Wall Street analysts to answer to, but they&#8217;re still under the gun to increase profits because if they don&#8217;t, they&#8217;re not given a golden parachute and exiled to a mansion in the Hamptons, they&#8217;re killed. So pointing them to greener pastures is a very lucrative business and no one is better at it than Olivia Olson.<br />
Liz: Why are you telling me all this? You&#8217;re usually annoyingly guarded about your true motive for giving us a case. Why are you admitting that you&#8217;re giving us this criminal to expand?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because it&#8217;s a win-win. I get to expand my reach, and you get to know more about what Anna McMahon has been up to.<br />
Liz: Are you telling me Olson has intel on Anna McMahon?<br />
<b>Red:</b> As I said, it&#8217;s a win-win.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ] [ Liz briefs Cooper, Ressler and Aram, who is looking sullen ]<br />
Cooper: Reddington wants the Task Force to go after a Blacklister who works with Anna McMahon when Anna McMahon is overseeing the Task Force.<br />
Liz: I know. It&#8217;s tricky.<br />
Ressler: The tricky part is knowing if we&#8217;re getting played. Figuring out if this Olson woman is involved in McMahon&#8217;s plot against this country or whether Reddington just said that so we&#8217;d have incentive to take out his competition.<br />
Liz: It&#8217;s incentive enough for me. We are nowhere on figuring out what McMahon is doing. She&#8217;s a top-level justice department official who has the ear of the President and is orchestrating a conspiracy so dangerous she had to hire a hit man to kill the people who found out. [ Red is napping. Dembe walks over with a laptop, waking Red up ]<br />

[ Red grimaces, presses a key gingerly ]<br />
Aram: $273. That&#8217;s the interest per hour on $60 million. $2.4 million a year, $6,575 a day, $273 an hour.<br />
<b>Red:</b> At 4%.<br />
Aram: I was being generous. The federal funds rate is 2.5.<br />
[ Red drinks ] [ GROANS, INHALES SHARPLY ]<br />

[ Aram types ] [ KEYBOARD CLACKING ] </p>

That&#8217;s a heavy burden to bear, even if the path one chooses is the only one in sight. It&#8217;s the burden Samar now bears. She didn&#8217;t leave because she thought you would come to resent her. She left because she saw no other path. She&#8217;s a target. And if she was in your life, you&#8217;d be a target, too. So she left. Allow her to believe she did the right thing. If you go to her, she&#8217;ll just have to leave you again. Don&#8217;t make her burden heavier than she can bear.<br />
Aram: Samar is the strongest person I know.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And yet she didn&#8217;t have the strength to say goodbye to you. You are more powerful than you know, Aram. Use it wisely.</p>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:16 Lady Luck (‚Ññ 69)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): The case of Olivia Olson (Blacklister #115) has given The Reddington Task Force its first lead on the plot by DOJ‚Äôs Deputy Attorney General Anna McMahon (and even the President, Robert Diaz) against the interests United States. Red gave the task force the case to get access to Olson‚Äôs case files for Cooper, but also to take out some of his own competition, since Olson specialized in identifying criminal enterprises ripe for hostile takeovers. The operation worked and the task force broke up Olson‚Äôs business. As Red surmised, Olson had McMahon as a client. Since McMahon now supervises the task force, Cooper handed over to her Olson‚Äôs case files but ‚Äì unbeknowst to her ‚Äì kept a copy. When McMahon returned the file, there was one case missing, titled ‚ÄúThe Third Estate.‚Äù </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s a reference to the French Revolution. It means ‚Äúeveryone else.‚Äù The 99%. It also means McMahon used Olson to pressure the Third Estate into helping McMahon carry out her plot against the United States.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Meanwhile, Red was able to convince Aram that Samar‚Äôs leaving was in her and his best interests, though painful. But Aram owes Red $56K+ for the interest Red charged him for stealing $60M of his from the Bank Vertrauen in Luxembourg. (Aram had hoped to use Red‚Äôs money as leverage to get Red to take him to Samar.)
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A shipping depot ]<br />
[ Men are ARGUING IN NATIVE LANGUAGE (Nigerian, Albanian) ]<br />
[ Red and Dembe get out of a car ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ WHISTLES ] Hey! Guys, come on. Guys. Let&#8217;s just simmer down.<br />
[ ARGUING STOPS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What&#8217;s the problem here?<br />
[ ARGUING RESUMES ]<br />
Dembe: You see what I mean?<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ LAUGHS ] What are they fighting about?<br />
Dembe: It&#8217;s the first shipment of a $3-million order. There&#8217;s a dispute over some doctored shipping manifests that are missing.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Who was in charge of the manifest?<br />
Dembe: Henry Morris. He works for the Department of Transportation.<br />
Man: Henry!<br />
<b>Red:</b> The one with the gambling habit?<br />
Dembe: The same.<br />
<b>Red:</b>: Didn&#8217;t we square his debt, get him some kind of help or something? Where the hell is he?<br />
Dembe: Not answering.<br />
[ GUNS COCKING ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey, hey! Oh. All right. Hey, hey. Come on. Come on, come on. Guys, put the guns away. Put the guns away. Come on. It&#8217;s just a bunch of TVs. [ LAUGHS ] There&#8217;s plenty more where they came from. Dembe, let&#8217;s see if we can&#8217;t drum up a few bottles of arak.<br />
‚Äî Arak.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yeah, there we go. All right.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Henry Morris sits at a bar in Atlantic City NJ playing cards on an electronic screen ] [ BEEPING ]<br />
[ Sad music plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Life seems lonely<br />
And I&#8217;m by myself
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ An elderly woman sitting next to him speaks up ]<br />
Agathe Tyche: Can&#8217;t be all that bad, can it?<br />
Henry: Bad?<br />
[ Bartender pours ] [ LIQUID POURING ]<br />
Henry: How about my savings, my house? And my wife has no idea.<br />
Agathe:  You&#8217;ll think of something, Henry.<br />
Henry: How&#8217;d you know my name?<br />
Agathe: I know all about you. The default on your mortgage, the credit cards. Oh, not to mention what you owe Tony and the boys in Boston. Heck, they haven&#8217;t forgotten.<br />
Henry: Who the hell are you? Who told you that?<br />
Agathe: Oh, that&#8217;s not important. You know what is important? Luck. And yours just changed.<br />
Henry: I&#8217;m supposed to be somewhere.<br />
Agathe: No. Henry. You&#8217;re meant to be right here. With me. And all you have to do is make one more bet. This time on yourself.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The shipping depot ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, boys. Thanks, guys. There really is no misunderstanding that a bottle of arak can&#8217;t cut through.<br />
[ SPEAKING NATIVE LANGUAGE ]<br />
[ CELLPHONE RINGING ]<br />
Dembe: It&#8217;s him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ On phone ] Henry. Five Albanians and four Nigerians walk into a shipping depot. There is no punch line. Where the hell are you?<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:17 The Third Estate (‚Ññ 136)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red has been cleaning house, cracking down on associates in his network who took advantage of his time in prison to freelance. One group, including Smokey Putnam, had even diverted Red‚Äôs assets to traffick methamphetamines, which Red heartily disapproves of. Those miscreants Red killed. Red is also questioning these associates to see if they had turned him in to the police. All have denied it, so Red has amped up the pressure by killing Smokey in a dramatic way (dropping him from his airplane) to ‚Äúsend a message‚Äù to anyone who knew who betrayed him to come forward. He explained his rationale to Dembe ~ placing Dembe in a dilemma since Dembe knows it was Liz who turned Red in. Liz begged Dembe not to tell Red and (so far) Dembe has kept Liz‚Äôs secret.</p>
<p>Liz has been able to let go the entire matter of Red‚Äôs true identity, but Ressler has continued to pursue it, leaning on a friend in the CIA, MJ Ward, who had run point on the CIA‚Äôs efforts years earlier to find out what had happened to Liz‚Äôs mother, Katarina Rostova. It has long been assumed that Katarina died by suicide, but there have been a couple of possible sightings over the years. Together, Ressler and Ward followed up on one of them which has turned up someone who may be Katarina‚Äôs mother, 81, now living under the alias of Virginia Lopatin in Chicago.</p>
<p>In the matter of the plot of DOJ Deputy Director Anna McMahon (and President Robert Diaz) against the interests of the United States, Red directed the task force to look into one of his associates, Henry Morris (a gambler who became a target of Blacklister #69 Lady Luck), who informed Liz that he had done some work for the code-named group ‚ÄúThe Third Estate.‚Äù Cooper had found the case of ‚ÄúThe Third Estate‚Äù in the files of hostile-taker artist Olivia Olson (Blacklister #115). Liz found out Henry Morris had set up state-of-the-art surveillance equipment for ‚ÄúThe Third Estate‚Äù to allow for hacking into high-end security systems in private homes.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A black Mercedes G-wagon without license plates drives under an elevated train track and pulls into a garage. The driver puts on a <i>papier m√¢ch√©</i> mask made with newspaper scraps and pulls back a partition separating him from two passengers, a middle-aged man and woman. The male passenger is Jacob Mercer, a wealthy businessman; the woman is his business manager, Susan Pelt ]<br />
Masked Driver: Get out. Through the door, up the stairs. She&#8217;s waiting.<br />
[ They follow his instructions ]<br />
Jacob Mercer: Hello? Hello?<br />
Zoey Mercer: [ Sobbing ]<br />
Jacob Mercer: Where is she? Please! I&#8217;m begging you!<br />
Zoey: Help, Dad!<br />
Jacob Mercer: Oh, my God.<br />
[ Another masked face appears on a large screen ]<br />
Masked Man: [ Distorted voice ] That&#8217;s far enough.<br />
Jacob: Zoey, are you okay?<br />
[ Zoey is tied to a torture rack. The ropes are tightened ]<br />
Zoey: [ Screams ]<br />
Jacob: Please, let her down.<br />
Masked Man: You brought the business manager?<br />
Jacob: Yes. She, uh, has the laptop, just like you said.<br />
Masked Man: Did you know, Susan, that the richest 26 people on Earth have as much wealth as the poorest 3.8 billion? I find your boss&#8217; wealth to be an act of immorality, so my friends and I are going to redistribute it in small amounts to those who need it more.<br />
Jacob: I-I will give you whatever you want if you just please let Zoey down.<br />
Masked Man: Sitting in the Fidelity Savings and Trust account is an $8.6-million bonus that Jacob was given for stopping the attempted unionization of his employees. I want it.<br />
Jacob: You‚Äì Wait. Hang on, Susan. Can we talk about this?<br />
Masked Man: Wrong answer.<br />
[ The ropes tighten ]<br />
Zoey: [ Screams ]<br />
Jacob: Okay, okay, okay! Just, stop!<br />
Masked Man: You have my routing numbers, Susan?<br />
Jacob: Fine.<br />
Zoey: [ Screaming ] Ow! Ah! Ah!<br />
Jacob: It&#8217;s done. Now just let her go.<br />
Masked Man: Not quite. But your firm has $36 million at First Brooklyn Savings Bank. It&#8217;s the surplus from your corporate tax cut, money your board of directors intends to use to buy back stocks and boost profits at the expense of workers. I want it.<br />
Jacob: Okay, no. I can&#8217;t do that. I don&#8217;t have authorization to‚Äì<br />
Masked Man: Susan does.<br />
Jacob: If we can talk about this‚Äì<br />
[ Ropes tighten ]<br />
Zoey: [ Screams ]<br />
Jacob: I- No, no, stop. Stop! I just- I said stop!<br />
Zoey: [ Crying ] Daddy! Please!<br />
Jacob: Okay. Fine.<br />
Zoey: Please, please, please!<br />
Masked Man: Thank you both. I can assure you these assets will be redistributed in a thoughtful manner to those in need. Zoey, thank you. Jacob, you can have your daughter back.<br />
Zoey: [ Sobbing ]<br />
[ The ropes are relaxed. Jacob runs to his daughter ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A rustic house in St Charles IL ] [ Ressler knocks. Door opens ]<br />
Ressler: Ted King? Donald Ressler, FBI. I was hoping to have a word with you and your wife.<br />
Ted King: Is something wrong?<br />
Ressler: Just a few questions. Uh, may I come in? Is your wife at home?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ted King: My wife had been sick for some time. Cancer. By the time the doctors found it, it was too late.<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;m very sorry for your loss.<br />
Ted King: No need to be sorry. We had a good life, Virginia and I.<br />
Ressler: Well, I&#8217;m here to ask you about Katarina.<br />
Ted King: Who?<br />
Ressler: Your stepdaughter, Katarina Rostova.<br />
Ted King: I don&#8217;t know who that is.<br />
Ressler: Now, Mr. King, if you expect me to believe that you don&#8217;t know‚Äì<br />
Ted King: Well, I don&#8217;t care what you believe. If my wife had a daughter, I think I&#8217;d know. What is this anyway? Why are you here?<br />
Ressler: We believe that your wife&#8217;s daughter from a previous marriage may be able to help us identify and capture the number one on our most wanted list, Raymond Reddington. Now, about Katarina‚Äì<br />
[ Ressler shows Ted King a photo of Katarina ]<br />
Ted King: I&#8217;m sorry you came all this way, but I don&#8217;t know who this is. If my wife had a child from a previous relationship, she never told me. I hope you find this character you&#8217;re looking for. I really do. But I&#8217;m afraid I can&#8217;t help you.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red‚Äôs flat ] [ Doorbell rings ] [ Red opens the door. He‚Äôs holding a gun behind his back ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Please, come in.<br />
Liz: This is a first‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have a lead ‚Äì<br />
Liz: ‚ÄìYou answering the door?<br />
<b>Red:</b> ‚Äì The Third Estate ‚Äì<br />
Liz: Where&#8217;s Dembe?<br />
[ Red puts the gun in a drawer while Liz goes around the flat looking for Dembe ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I know why they procured the surveillance equipment to help them breach security systems favored by the aristocrac‚Äì Are you listening?<br />
[ Liz comes back ]<br />
Liz: In the six years I&#8217;ve known you, I can count on one hand the amount of times I&#8217;ve seen you without Dembe, so, yeah, I&#8217;m listening, for an answer to my question.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dembe and I are having a bit of a disagreement over methodology. He thinks I&#8217;m being heavy-handed.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Dembe is at a mosque praying ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Liz: About what?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Finding the person who turned me in to the police. He&#8217;s been unusually oppositional. I suggested he take some time to more thoroughly reflect on my way of thinking.<br />
Liz: Which is?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A top advisor to the President is orchestrating a plot against your country. She&#8217;s engaged the Third Estate to help her. Why? And who are they? During the French Revolution, they were the 99%. Their goal was to behead the 1% in order to create a more perfect union. Sound familiar?<br />
Liz: Our 99% wants to soak the rich, not kill them.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell that to the billionaires whose children the Third Estate has abducted from their homes.<br />
Liz: The surveillance equipment.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Five abductions in the past 18 months, ransomed for hundreds of millions of dollars.<br />
Liz: That&#8217;s terrible, but I seriously doubt kidnapping rich kids is the plot against America Anna McMahon is orchestrating.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Or perhaps it&#8217;s a way to finance something more diabolical. Either way, it&#8217;s a symptom of where the world is right now, the rage of the many against the few.<br />
Liz: Like the rage you have against the person who turned you in.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Both are indomitable.<br />
Liz: Anna McMahon oversees all our cases. So if we bring this to her, she&#8217;s gonna know we&#8217;re going after her.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, that&#8217;d be perfectly awkward. I almost wish I could be there to see the expression on her face when she finds out.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Anna McMahon: The Third Estate?<br />
Liz: You&#8217;ve heard of them?<br />
McMahon: I think they were mentioned in an intel briefing. Domestic political agitators. Small potatoes.<br />
Liz: According to Reddington, they&#8217;ve kidnapped the children of some of the wealthiest people in the country.<br />
Aram: Zoey Mercer, Oliver Paige, Matt Ford, Mia Walker, and Des Foy. Scions of oil, real estate, pharmaceuticals, and finance.<br />
McMahon: These are high-profile scions from high-profile families. If their kids had been abducted, why didn&#8217;t we know about it?<br />
Liz: Because they threatened to kill them if they told anyone, so they made payments in private.<br />
McMahon: And the children? Were they safely returned?<br />
Cooper: Four of them were, after their parents paid nearly $300 million.<br />
McMahon: And the fifth?<br />
Ressler: Des Foy was taken two days ago.<br />
Liz: Unlike the others, his parents refused to make the secret settlement and went straight to the NYPD.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Des Foy is blindfolded and is being strapped to the rack ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Cooper: Aram, talk to the department. Tell them we will assist. Keen, Ressler, talk to the Foys. I want options on how to get their son back, and I want them fast.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: So much for small potatoes.<br />
McMahon: Why&#8217;d he bring you this case?<br />
Cooper: I don&#8217;t know or care. A life hangs in the balance. That&#8217;s reason enough for me.<br />
McMahon: He has a reason. I&#8217;ve read your case files. He always has a reason.<br />
Cooper: Yes. Or a target.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Foys‚Äô mansion in the countryside ]<br />
[ Liz and Ressler watch a video sent to the Foys ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
[ On the video, Des Foy is tied to the rack. He winces and moans ]<br />
Masked Man: Your son tells me you hate going into the city. But tomorrow, you&#8217;re gonna cross the river and see how the other half lives. There&#8217;s a bus station at 136th and Lincoln. Be there at 11:00 a.m., come alone, or your son dies.<br />
Des Foy: [ Sobs ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>Ressler: How long ago did he call?<br />
David Foy: I&#8217;m not paying!<br />
Evelyn Foy: About an hour.<br />
David: Not one goddamn penny!<br />
Evelyn: Don&#8217;t listen to him. Please don&#8217;t listen to him. We&#8217;ll pay.<br />
Ressler: If you go through with the ransom drop, we can use your money to lure them in.<br />
David: Five kids have been taken. And you know why they keep on doing it? Because it works. If we give in, someone else&#8217;s kid will be next. I am not capitulating to terrorists!<br />
Evelyn: I don&#8217;t care. I want my son.<br />
Ressler: Negotiation isn&#8217;t capitulation. The longer you string them along, the more opportunities we&#8217;ll have to locate your son.<br />
Liz: You have every right to be angry. And when you&#8217;re angry, it&#8217;s difficult to trust people. But you can trust us. Our only interest is Des&#8217; safety.<br />
David: I&#8217;m not paying the ransom. But, if you think it&#8217;ll help get him back, I will be on that bench tomorrow.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ At the mosque. Dembe walks with the imam ]<br />
Dembe: As-Salaam-Alaikum, imam.<br />
Imam: Na&#8217;eem tells me you rented out his entire restaurant for Ramadan.<br />
Dembe: I wanted to sponsor a few iftars for the community.<br />
Imam: Now, you know I appreciate all your contributions. You basically built our new tea room. But I wish I saw less of your checks and more of you. You look troubled.<br />
Dembe: I&#8217;ve lived by blind faith even when I don&#8217;t like what I see. I&#8217;m not sure I can do that anymore.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ]<br />
Ressler: The Foys are playing ball.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ve already alerted a TAC unit.<br />
Aram: Surveillance vans with audio feeds are prepped and ready to go. Mr. Foy will be wearing a tracker.<br />
Ressler: Are we gonna need Mother Superior&#8217;s okay?<br />
Cooper: I think where she&#8217;s concerned, we&#8217;ll go with seeking forgiveness rather than asking permission.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Anna McMahon: [ On phone ] I told you, it&#8217;s under control.<br />
Mr Sandquist: They suspect you.<br />
McMahon: Which is why I&#8217;m here. So it never amounts to more than suspicion.<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:18 The Brockton College Killer (‚Ññ 92)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): It turned out DOJ Deputy Director Anna McMahon was not behind The Third Estate (Blacklister #136) after all. Rather, McMahon left a trail of breadcrumbs for the task force to follow. Now she knows they are watching her and they know she is watching them, making the task force‚Äôs aim of stopping her plot against America more difficult than ever. </p>
<p>Dembe has sought spiritual counsel from his Imam to deal with his difficulty with Red‚Äôs amped up determination to figure out who turned him in to the police. Dembe found out that it was Liz, who had wanted to waylay Red so she (and her half-sister Jennifer/Lilly) could investigate his true identity. Liz begged Dembe to keep this a secret from Red but now Red has let the word out that he is willing to kill even his own associates to force anyone who knows who it was who turned him in to come forward. So Dembe went to Liz and told her she must tell Red it was her ‚Äì or he will.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, although Liz has decided it no longer matters to her who Red really is or why he took on the identity of her father, the real Raymond Reddington, Ressler picked up the trail. His idea was to find out what happened to Liz‚Äôs mother, the Russian spy, Katarina Rostova. He tracked Katarina‚Äôs mother (Liz‚Äôs maternal grandmother) to a town in Illinois. Although she had recently died of cancer, her widower said she had sent a letter just before she died. Ressler followed the letter to a PO box in remote Wilmington NY. Surveillance footage shows the letter was picked up Dominic Wilkinson (code-named ‚ÄúOleander‚Äù when he was with the KGB). He is Liz‚Äôs grandfather and the father of Katarina Rostova, and likely Virginia‚Äôs first husband.</p>
<p>Ressler doesn‚Äôt recognize Dom. Liz met him once while looking for her mother. Dom told her said he had known Katarina, but did not tell Liz he was Katarina‚Äôs father. Dom is also who Red had gone to to burn the bones of the real Raymond Reddington, thinking the secret of his true identity was sealed forever.
</p></blockquote>

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:19 Rassvet</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Fearing that if she did not come forward, Red would kill an innocent man, Liz has finally told Red that it was she, in league with her half-sister Jennifer, who turned Red in to the police and put his life at risk. He is furious, although, he says, not entirely surprised. He had learned that she had been in looking for the nurse of plastic surgeon Dr. Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33) and thought she likely knew that he was ‚Äúonce someone else‚Äù and that Dr Koehler had performed surgery on him that allowed him to assume the identity of her dead father, the real Raymond Reddington. Red‚Äôs anger is compounded by Dembe‚Äôs betrayal ~ Dembe who, though disapproving, had kept Liz‚Äôs secret from him. Liz tells Red she no longer cares about his true identity: ‚ÄúI came face-to-face with losing you, and I realized that I don&#8217;t care about who you were ‚Äì I care for who you are. And that&#8217;s the only thing that matters.‚Äù</p>
<p>Unassuaged, Red goes to see Dom (Dominic Wilkinson), Liz‚Äôs maternal grandfather who recounts the betrayal he felt when his daughter Katarina Rostova became a traitor to her country (the USSR) at the end of the Cold War. He said it was his love for her that allowed him to give up everything ‚Äì job, home, family, country ‚Äì and move to America where his connection with her still makes him a target of Russian agents and requires him to live as a recluse. Red returns home feeling reconciled ‚Äì only to find out Dembe has visited his Imam and has decided to leave his service as Red‚Äôs bodyguard, a bitter disappointment for Red.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Ressler finally spills to Liz that he has kept up the search for Red‚Äôs identity without her knowledge. He discovered that her maternal grandmother who had recently died had tried to send a letter to her daughter Katarina via a P.O. Box in Wilmington in Upstate New York. He has a photo from surveillance footage of the man who picked up the letter. But he says the search had come up short and that the man is ‚Äúa ghost.‚Äù But Liz recognizes the man in the photo. It is Dom and she met him once in an earlier attempt to find out about her mother and Red. But Dom didn‚Äôt tell her ar the time that he was her grandfather, only that he had been a Russian asset. So, she pays him a visit. ‚Ä¶
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

[ TICKING CONTINUES ]<br />

I have proof. What happened in those 6 months between the night the world thinks my mother drowned and the day Reddington came back from the dead? What happened?<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Cape May, about 30 years earlier ] [ WIND RUSHING, CHIMES CLINKING ] [ WAVES CRASHING, BIRDS CALLING ]<br />

Katarina: Money in secret accounts. Paper trails of payoffs. Passports in safety-deposit boxes ‚Äì evidence that I didn&#8217;t steal his secrets, but that he shared them with me.<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:20 Guillermo Rizal (‚Ññ 128)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Ressler‚Äôs search for the Red‚Äôs true identity bore fruit. He did not find Liz‚Äôs mother, Katarina Rostova herself, but he was able to trace a lead to a man who might be her grandfather. Showing Liz a grainy photo from surveillance footage, he says he came up short and was able to find no further information on the man. But Liz recognizes him as Dominic (Dom) Wilkinson, a former asset for Russian intelligence who she has met earlier in her search, but he did not let her know then he  was her maternal grandfather. She knew where to find him in rural Upstate New York and what a tale he had to tell.</p>
<p>Katarina did not drown in the ocean at Cape May. She intended to, but it was instead a ‚Äúbaptism,‚Äù according to Dom. She stumbled out of the ocean and landed at a women‚Äôs shelter where she recovered. Still hunted by the KGB, the Cabal and the Americans ‚Äì all whom she had betrayed ‚Äì she turned to a childhood friend, Ilya Koslov ‚Äì who suggested a bold plan, for him to take on the identity of Raymond Reddington, with whom Katarina had had an affair ‚Äì and a child (Masha, or Liz). During a fight over her, Masha had shot her father. Ilya had helped Katarina try to save Reddington‚Äôs life and when that failed, to dispose of his body. Because Reddington had been Katarina‚Äôs asset, blackmail money ‚Äì $40 million ‚Äì had been deposited in various banks around Europe, but only could be withdrawn by Reddington personally. So, with the help of plastic surgeon Dr Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33), Ilya Koslov, a young bureaucrat at the Russian Embassy adept at creating fake documents, became Reddington to access the money which would allow Katarina and her parents to ‚Äúdisappear‚Äù and begin new lives. </p>
<p>Katarina‚Äôs parents were saved, but Katarina herself disappeared with a passport identifying her as Anna Croft. Ilya stepped into the shoes of Raymond Reddington, a man destined to be an international pariah ‚Äì with the KGB, the Cabal and American Intelligence all eager to disparage his reputation. But Ilya‚Äôs devotion to Katarina was unconditional and he readily agreed to watch over Masha until Katarina re-emerged. But she didn‚Äôt. According to Dom, he last saw her 28 years ago, at the Postal Elite in Upstate Wilmington, New York, when he gave her the key to P.O. Box 642. </p>
<p>Liz flew to Hong Kong to inform Red of her knowledge of his true identity. He was not pleased, blaming her search for invading his privacy and for destroying his relationship with Dembe, who has left him. Red goes to Dom to confront him, insisting Dom tell him ‚Äúevery word‚Äù of what he shared with Liz and insisting that even so many years later, his story (and Katarina‚Äôs and Liz‚Äôs) being ‚Äúthrown out there into the ether‚Äù can only mean trouble.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A children‚Äôs arcade in Minneapolis MN ]<br />
[ Crystal Fighters&#8217; ‚ô™ &#8220;Wild Ones&#8221; plays ]</p>
<blockquote><p>

Adults were only three feet tall. As a result, they consumed less, had a smaller carbon footprint. If we&#8217;re going to survive climate change, we have to adapt to our environment the same way Homo floresiensis adapted to theirs. I want us to survive. To do that, we have to evolve. And since we don&#8217;t have time to wait on natural selection, I figured out a way to speed up the process.<br />

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:21 Anna McMahon (‚Ññ 60)</h2>

Program air date: 5/10/2019 in the US<br />

<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:21 Anna McMahon (‚Ññ 60)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Red and the Task Force are in a race with DOJ official Anna McMahon to find a ‚Äúrandom child‚Äù with whom Bastien Moreau (Blacklister #20) left the single remaining copy of a dossier detailing a plot by McMahon and sleezy President Robert Diaz against the United States. </p>
<p>Red remains angry at Liz for having dug up information about who he was before he took on the identity of her father, the real Raymond Reddington. In his previous life, he was Ilya Koslov, a bureaucrat at the Russian Embassy in DC. Ilya was a childhood friend of Liz‚Äôs mother Katarina Rostova. According to Liz, Katarina and Ilya later were also ‚Äúin the Cabal together.‚Äù At the end of the Cold War, as alliances collapsed, they were on the run from the KGB, the Cabal and the Americans. In order the get at money deposited in Reddington‚Äôs name, Ilya took on Reddington‚Äôs identity after he had been shot by Liz (‚ÄúMasha‚Äù) who, as a child on 4 or so had shot him to stop a fight between him and Katarina over her. Plastic surgeon Dr Hans Koehler (Blacklister #33) performed a series of surgeries on Ilya to change his appearance to that of Reddington. This allowed him to access $40 million deposited in various banks that had been put there to blackmail Reddington. The KGB and the Cabal subsequently destroyed Reddington‚Äôs reputation so no one would believe his evidence against him and he went on the run and built his criminal empire. Katarina and Ilya gave Katarina‚Äôs parents new identities in America. Katarina‚Äôs mother recently died but Liz‚Äôs grandfather is alive, living under the identity of Dominic Wilkinson (‚ÄúDom‚Äù). He was a former KBG operative, who was also Katarina‚Äôs handler. He had ordered Katarina to have a relationship with Reddington, a US Naval Intelligence operative. Instead, she had a child with him, Masha (or Liz).</p>
<p>Liz shared Red‚Äôs true identity with Ressler who had helped in her search, but they have agreed to tell no one else since Red and Dom are still being hunted by those he betrayed. What happened to Katarina remains a mystery. Red‚Äôs anger at Liz is profound, but she is off-limits to his usual code of ethics (which would mean he would have to kill her for betraying him) because of a promise he made to Katarina to take care of her, a pledge grounded in his complete devotion to Katarina. Besides, as Cooper points out, there is love and trust between Red and Liz as they are ‚Äúfamily‚Äù in the deepest sense despite family squabbles.</p>
<p>Liz has been reassured by the ‚Äúsweet‚Äù story of Katarina and Ilya‚Äôs past and tells Red she is now comfortable enough with who he was to bring her daughter Agnes home from the care her paternal grandmother Scottie. Dembe, Red‚Äôs longtime bodyguard and friend, though forgiven by Red for hiding Liz‚Äôs search from him, has left him, a move that has caused Red‚Äôs torture-master Brimley to upbraid Red and challenge his code of ethics as nothing more than ‚Äúlipstick on a pig‚Äù and ‚Äútrayf.‚Äù
</p></blockquote>

Ressler: Take him! I&#8217;m going after Sandquist!<br />
Liz: [ To Jonathan ] Hang on. Hang on.<br />
Jonathan: [ GASPING ]<br />
Liz: Hey. Hey. Shh. Don&#8217;t talk. We&#8217;ve got help on the way. Shh.<br />
Jonathan: Pocket ‚Äì<br />
[ Liz reaches inside Jonathan‚Äôs inside suit jacket pocket and pulls out the envelope with the dossier inside. But Jonathan is dying ]<br />
Liz: [ Pleading ] Listen to me. You hear my voice? Hang on. Stay with us. Hey! Stay with us.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper‚Äôs office ] [ FOOTSTEPS APPROACH ~ It‚Äôs Red ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> [ Jovially ] Don&#8217;t you love the anticipation? The moment before the curtain goes up, wondering if the show will live up to all the hype and expectation.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;m rooting for underwhelming.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Aww.<br />
Cooper: Whatever Intel the dossier contains, too many people have been killed to keep it secret. Jon Grimm. Christopher Miles. Ana Ziegler. You were nearly killed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I never properly thanked you for making sure that didn&#8217;t happen.<br />
Cooper: I was doing my job.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Harold. You respect authority. You follow the chain of command. And yet you marched into the White House and ordered the President to stay my execution.<br />
Cooper: Desperate times ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> What you did wasn&#8217;t a desperate measure. It was an act of bravery and friendship. I can count on one hand the number of people to whom I owe my life. You are one of them. For that, I am forever grateful.<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ]<br />
Aram: They&#8217;re here.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Ressler: Aram.<br />
[ Ressler tosses the drive with the dossier to Aram who plugs the drive into his computer ]<br />

[ The link brings up a video of Christopher Miles, now deceased. At the time the video was made he was a former MI6 Agent. The video was meant for Anna Ziegler, head of German Intelligence (BND), also now deceased. Both were killed by Bastien Moreau under contract to Anna McMahon ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Christopher Miles:</b> Madam Ziegler, if you&#8217;re watching this, it&#8217;s only because your people have vetted my story. </p></blockquote>
<p>Cooper: Wait. Diaz&#8217;s plan is to assassinate‚Äì<br />
Liz: Himself?<br />
<b>Red:</b> So much for underwhelming.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Christopher Miles:</b> Contained in this dossier are the cables, intercepts, and secret sources I&#8217;ve used to unravel this plot.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Aram: There is a lot of data-sourcing here. </p>
<blockquote><p>
To the best of my knowledge, the operation appears to be led by Anna McMahon, a high-ranking official in the Justice Department. I believe McMahon, along with select others, are working in concert with members of the President&#8217;s security detail.
</p></blockquote>
<p>Ressler: He doesn&#8217;t sound like he thinks the President is in on this.</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Christopher Miles:</b> I don&#8217;t know exactly why this is happening or who initiated the hit, but I do know the when and where. President Diaz and his opponent will be conducting a series of presidential debates. I have reason to believe the hit will be carried out during one of them.<br />
I&#8217;m not sure who I can trust within the U.S. government, which is why I&#8217;m coming to you. Because we have a history. Because I can trust you. And because I think you have the best chance to save Robert Diaz&#8217;s life.
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: All right. There are three debates. One last month, one next month and one tomorrow at the Fillmont.<br />
<b>Red:</b> See if the Third Estate pulled a permit to protest outside.<br />
Liz: You told us McMahon had nothing to do with them.<br />
<b>Red:</b> She doesn&#8217;t. But perhaps she wanted us to think she did.<br />
Cooper: Why? And how does it fit in now?<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Third Estate are domestic terrorists dedicated to bringing down the rich and powerful.<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m sorry, but, uh, am I understanding this correctly? The American President is part of a plot to assassinate himself.<br />
Liz: It doesn&#8217;t make any sense.<br />
Ressler: I&#8217;m sorry. What are we missing here?<br />
Liz: He&#8217;s not gonna kill himself.<br />
Aram: Uh, okay, well, it looks like the Third Estate will be protesting at the venue.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course they will. They hate Diaz. McMahon needs a patsy. Who better to blame for decapitating the head of state than a group named after people who decapitated heads of state?<br />
Cooper: The debate is tomorrow. That gives us a day to figure out how to prevent the assassination.<br />
Liz: But if the President supposedly wants this to happen, we can&#8217;t inform him or the Secret Service.<br />
Cooper: So we&#8217;re on our own. And we&#8217;re on a clock. I want the blueprints to that venue and the path to Diaz&#8217;s motorcade. I don&#8217;t care if the President is involved in the plot to assassinate himself or not. Our job is to keep that from happening.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Mr Sandquist has just had his gunshot wound bandaged ]<br />
Anna McMahon: POTUS is about two minutes out.<br />
Mr Sandquist: It&#8217;s over. They have the dossier.<br />
McMahon: We don&#8217;t know that. Listen to me.<br />
Sandquist: Listening to you got me shot and five of my men killed. They know.<br />
McMahon: Which is why we can&#8217;t call it off. If we do, they&#8217;ll arrest us and we&#8217;ll hang for treason.<br />
Sandquist: We are gonna hang for treason.<br />
McMahon: Not if someone else takes the blame.<br />
Sandquist: The Third Estate can&#8217;t save us now.<br />
McMahon: No. Only Reddington can.<br />
Sandquist: Reddington.<br />
McMahon: We can get what we want. And take him down once and for all. But if POTUS knows that we lost the dossier, he&#8217;ll get cold feet. Diaz cannot know the truth. Milian, listen to me. I know we haven&#8217;t always agreed on tactics, but you have to trust me on this one.<br />
[ President Diaz enters ]<br />
Diaz: How do you feel?<br />
Sandquist: Fine, sir.<br />
Diaz: Next question. And this time I want an honest answer. Did you get it?<br />
Sandquist: ‚Äì Yes, sir. We did.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The Post Office ] [ Liz talks to Red on her cell phone; she is alone ]<br />
Liz: Please tell me this makes sense to you. The President conspiring to kill himself?<br />
<b>Red:</b> He took foreign money to get elected. If he did that, who knows what else he&#8217;s done. Maybe people found out, and the walls are closing in, and he prefers to go out as a martyr to the cause. Many presidents only live for their legacy. Whatever the reason, he&#8217;s carrying a heavy burden. People who kill themselves always are. Burdens they can&#8217;t imagine ever being able to cast off.<br />
Liz: Are you talking about the President or my mother?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Your mother was not as bad as‚Äì I understand why you might think she was, but she wasn&#8217;t. She was a young woman trying to make sense of a world that was falling apart around her. She was on one side of an unbridgeable divide. Your father was on the other. And you were in between. Over the years, your mother&#8217;s legend has grown. Mythic spy. Bloodless turncoat.<br />
In the process, people forgot the person behind the legend, but I haven&#8217;t. If she were here, I&#8217;m sure she&#8217;d tell you she made so many mistakes. She was scared and uncertain and just trying to do the best she could. Bring Agnes home, Elizabeth.<br />
Liz: If there&#8217;s any risk ‚Äì<br />
<b>Red:</b> There isn&#8217;t. Bring her home.<br />
Liz: [ EXHALES SHARPLY ] Thank you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> If you need me, I&#8217;ll be at Jin&#8217;s.<br />
Liz: Sinusitis acting up again?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Nah. Sciatica.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Elevator DOORS SLIDING ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m telling you, the man is a wizard.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Anna McMahon gets off the elevator with a large group of DHS Agents ]<br />
McMahon: Be sure to get all the case files, paperwork, electronics.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Agent: Sir, please put your hands where I can see them.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Agent: Agent Mojtabai, you&#8217;re under arrest for conspiracy to commit murder.<br />

Cooper: You&#8217;re trying to get us before we get you.<br />

<h2>üî¥ Script 6:22 Robert Diaz (‚Ññ 15)</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Program air date: 5/17/2019 in the US<br />
Script Permalink: <a href="https://wp.me/pDKwi-9Ei" rel="nofollow">https://wp.me/pDKwi-9Ei</a><br />

<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>‚≠ï Script 6:22 Robert Diaz (‚Ññ 15)</h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Brief</b> (Where we‚Äôre at): Just as the Task Force had nailed down proof of a plot against the United States led by players in the Department of Justice, Homeland Security, the Secret Service and President Robert Diaz himself, the tables were turned. Assistant Attorney General Anna McMahon (Blacklister #60) is going to blame the plot on the Task Force and has had DHS agents arrest Cooper, Ressler and Aram. Liz was out of sight so she avoided arrest for the time being. </p>
<p>The plot was described in a dossier left by Christopher Miles, a former MI6 Agent who shared his findings with the head of German Intelligence Ana Ziegler. Both were murdered at the behest of McMahon by Bastien Moreau (Blacklister #20).  McMahon has been desperate to round up the sole remaining physical copy of the dossier. She failed and the Task Force got to it first. It was at that point that she hatched the plan to turn the tables and blame the whole plot on the Task Force. </p>
<p>Inexplicable is the fact that the plot described in the dossier involves the assassination of the president. Yet the president is one of the plotters. Does he not know this particular detail? Is it a suicide arrangement of some kind? Is the plan to fake an assassination? The possibilities boggle the mind. But this seems irrelevant at this point, since the Task Force itself has suddenly been de-commissioned. Except for Liz and Red, of course, who have not been apprehended ‚Äì yet. Dembe is out of the picture, having left Red‚Äôs employ. Will he reappear? Red still has some leverage over President Robert Diaz ‚Äì knowledge that he took $300 million in illegal campaign contributions from ‚Äúa Russian oligarch‚Äù ‚Äì Liz‚Äôs stepfather, Alexander Kirk (aka Constantin Rostov) (Blacklister #14), who was married to her mother Katarina Rostova when Liz was born. Rostov disappeared after Red whispered something to him in Episode 3:23. What did he whisper? That Red is not the ‚ÄúRaymond Reddington‚Äù that Rostov so despised? ‚Äì a fact that we now know (or at least think we do). </p>
<p>What we know are hints and clues. The plot against America that is in play is code-named the ‚ÄúThe Princip Initiative,‚Äù named for Gavrilo Princip, the Bosnian Serb who assassinated Archduke Ferdinand of Austria. ‚ÄúThat single act set into motion the chain of events that ignited the First World War,‚Äù says Red. The First World War led inexorably to World War II which led to the Cold War which led the the collapse of the USSR, which puts Liz‚Äôs birth at the nexus of a hundred years of world history. As Red tells Liz about her mother: </p>
<blockquote><p>
She was a young woman trying to make sense of a world that was falling apart around her. She was on one side of an unbridgeable divide. Your father was on the other. And you were in between.
</p></blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i>[ ‚ãô Note: German dialogue from subtitles is in italics ]</i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The remaining personel are escorted from the central area (war room) of the ‚ÄòPost Office‚Äô black site. Cooper, Ressler and Aram were arrested earlier ]<br />
‚Äî This way.<br />
‚Äî Come on.<br />
‚Äî Let&#8217;s go.<br />
[ Senior DOJ official Anna McMahon makes a call from Cooper‚Äôs office, now vacant, to President Robert Diaz ]<br />
Anna McMahon: It&#8217;s handled.<br />
President Diaz: Except Keen and Reddington.<br />
McMahon: The less you know, the better.<br />
Diaz: Anna, I believe we&#8217;re way past plausible deniability.<br />
McMahon: They&#8217;ll come for their friends, and then we&#8217;ll have all the traitors.<br />
Diaz: You say that like it&#8217;ll be easy to prove. These are honest people‚Äì<br />
McMahon: Who have killed Secret Service Agents investigating a plot against the President. Whose work has made Reddington stronger. They&#8217;re in league with him, and he hates you. I&#8217;m not worried about making a case against them. The question I have is you. Do you want this?<br />
Diaz: We&#8217;ve talked about this.<br />
McMahon: I know. Before. But this is it. It&#8217;s your last chance to say no.<br />
Diaz: It&#8217;s what has to be done.<br />
McMahon: I can&#8217;t imagine how hard this must be for you.<br />
Diaz: One shot. A kill shot. That&#8217;s my instruction and I want it clearly conveyed.<br />
McMahon: A kill shot.<br />
Diaz: I&#8217;d like this to be as painless as possible.<br />
[ PHONE BEEPS ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ First Lady Miriam Diaz walks up to her husband ]<br />
Miriam: Tomorrow&#8217;s a big day for you.<br />
Diaz: For both of us. What you&#8217;ve wanted me to do, I&#8217;m gonna take care of it tomorrow at the debate.<br />
Miriam: Do you mean that?<br />
Diaz: This has haunted us for too long.<br />
Miriam: [ EXHALES SHAKILY ] I&#8217;m relieved to hear you say that.<br />
Diaz: Ohh. It&#8217;ll shock the world.<br />
Miriam: I don&#8217;t care about the world. I care about you. I know you&#8217;re conflicted, but this is the right thing to do. [ SIGHS ] And I&#8217;m proud of you for doing it.<br />
[ Hug ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Cooper is locked in an interrogation room ] [ INTERCOM BEEPS ]<br />
Anna McMahon: Agent Cooper. It&#8217;s over. Agent Keen&#8217;s badge was swiped. We know she&#8217;s in the facility, and we will find her. Main Justice has evidence that your Task Force is working with Reddington on a <i>coup d&#8217;etat.</i> Reddington will be hunted. Your team will be tried and convicted. But I&#8217;m willing to help you, Harold, only you ‚Äì if you reach out to her. Bring her in.<br />
[ McMahon holds up the flash drive with the dossier compiled by former MI6 Agent Christopher Miles detailing the assassination planned by McMahon and members of the Secret Service  ]<br />
McMahon: The Miles dossier. We recovered it from Agent Mojtabai&#8217;s computer. Without it you have nothing. Make the call. Bring her in.<br />
Cooper: Good luck.<br />
McMahon: Good luck?<br />
Cooper: You&#8217;re gonna need it if you hope to dismantle my team.<br />
McMahon: Your team is going to prison.<br />
Cooper: Then I&#8217;m going with them.<br />
McMahon: And Agent Keen? She won&#8217;t make it out of here alive.<br />
Cooper: You don&#8217;t know Agent Keen.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Liz calls Red from somewhere within the black site. Red is in his Mercedes ]<br />
Liz: Reddington.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth.<br />
Liz: McMahon has them. Cooper, Ressler, and Aram. Everyone. She has her people sweeping the building looking for me. I need your help. I have an idea.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You&#8217;ve gotten out of there before. You can do it again.<br />
Liz: I am not leaving them.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s nothing you can do for them right now.<br />
Liz: I don&#8217;t think you get it. I am getting my team out of here. We are stopping the President from killing himself ‚Äì and then I am going to the store for every princess pillow, comforter, backpack, toothbrush, and pajamas I can find so my apartment&#8217;s ready when Agnes gets home. Do you understand me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tell me what you need me to do.<br />
Liz: Put me in touch with your friend. Uh, the kid whose mother hates you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Tadashi Ito.<br />
Liz: Yeah. Tadashi. That&#8217;s it. Have him call me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll try. [ CHUCKLES ] But my arrangement with Mariko is weekends only. What else?<br />
Liz: How long do you think it&#8217;ll take Ruddiger to get here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ruddiger? I am not sure he&#8217;s even in the country.<br />
Liz: It isn&#8217;t just Ruddiger. He&#8217;s gonna need help.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Elizabeth, slow down. If I&#8217;m going to involve Ruddiger, I need to know exactly what you&#8217;re planning.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red goes to see Maxwell Ruddiger, a munitions wizard ]<br />
[ RADIO TUNING ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where the hell is everyone?<br />
Ruddiger: Ah. It&#8217;s, uh- It&#8217;s a work in progress.<br />
<b>Red:</b> A work in progress? Ruddiger! We don&#8217;t have time! I was very clear‚Äì<br />
Jurgen: <i>Where are the heatshrink connectors?</i><br />
Ruddiger: <i>I told you if they‚Äôre not with the pulse reset counters, then they are going to be in my strip-it bag.</i><br />
<b>Red:</b> Who&#8217;s this guy?<br />
Ruddiger: Jurgen.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Does Jurgen work at the airport?<br />
Jurgen: [ In perfect English ] Part time. Customer service.<br />
Ruddiger: He&#8217;s bilingual.<br />
[ A Tall Man and another man enter ]<br />
Ruddiger: <i>Where the hell have you been? I needed you here fifteen minutes ago!</i><br />
Tall Man: <i>We had to get the gear.</i><br />
<b>Red:</b> Ruddiger.<br />
Ruddiger: You said you needed a team.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And this is them?<br />
Ruddiger: Yeah.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Who are these guys?<br />

var WPGroHo = {"my_hash":""};
</script>
<script type='text/javascript' src='https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/mu-plugins/gravatar-hovercards/wpgroho.js?m=1380573781h'></script>

	<script>
		//initialize and attach hovercards to all gravatars
		jQuery( document ).ready( function( $ ) {

			if (typeof Gravatar === "undefined"){
				return;
			}

			if ( typeof Gravatar.init !== "function" ) {
				return;
			}			

			Gravatar.profile_cb = function( hash, id ) {
				WPGroHo.syncProfileData( hash, id );
			};
			Gravatar.my_hash = WPGroHo.my_hash;
			Gravatar.init( 'body', '#wp-admin-bar-my-account' );
		});
	</script>

		<div style="display:none">
	</div>
